n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ beta_support }}\n-\n-![/reference/images/switch-web.png](/reference/images/switch-web.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"Switch\", width=300) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/table.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/table.md\nindex 13a80e2a16..dc46eb2dd4 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/table.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/table.md\n@@ -1,72 +1,4 @@\n-# Table\n-\n-A widget for displaying columns of tabular data. Scroll bars will be provided if necessary.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/table-cocoa.png](/reference/images/table-cocoa.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux\n-\n-![/reference/images/table-gtk.png](/reference/images/table-gtk.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows\n-\n-![/reference/images/table-winforms.png](/reference/images/table-winforms.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android {{ beta_support }}\n-\n-![/reference/images/table-android.png](/reference/images/table-android.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"Table\", width=450) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/textinput.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/textinput.md\nindex bb862536d0..255e2e7e7d 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/textinput.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/textinput.md\n@@ -1,84 +1,4 @@\n-# TextInput\n-\n-A widget for the display and editing of a single line of text.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-cocoa.png](/reference/images/textinput-cocoa.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-gtk.png](/reference/images/textinput-gtk.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-winforms.png](/reference/images/textinput-winforms.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-android.png](/reference/images/textinput-android.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-iOS.png](/reference/images/textinput-iOS.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ beta_support }}\n-\n-![/reference/images/textinput-web.png](/reference/images/textinput-web.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ beta_support }}\n-\n-Screenshot not available\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"TextInput\", width=300) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/timeinput.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/timeinput.md\nindex 16304c8161..e4244b90e3 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/timeinput.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/timeinput.md\n@@ -1,78 +1,4 @@\n-# TimeInput\n-\n-A widget to select a clock time.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/timeinput-cocoa.png](/reference/images/timeinput-cocoa.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows\n-\n-![/reference/images/timeinput-winforms.png](/reference/images/timeinput-winforms.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android\n-\n-![/reference/images/timeinput-android.png](/reference/images/timeinput-android.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/timeinput-iOS.png](/reference/images/timeinput-iOS.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-![/reference/images/timeinput-web.png](/reference/images/timeinput-web.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"TimeInput\", width=300) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/tree.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/tree.md\nindex 00ec52a749..955d983427 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/tree.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/tree.md\n@@ -1,60 +1,4 @@\n-# Tree\n-\n-A widget for displaying a hierarchical tree of tabular data. Scroll bars will be provided if necessary.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/tree-cocoa.png](/reference/images/tree-cocoa.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux\n-\n-![/reference/images/tree-gtk.png](/reference/images/tree-gtk.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"Tree\", width=450) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/webview.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/webview.md\nindex cba5d7cbc9..4b79c58e44 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/webview.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/webview.md\n@@ -1,78 +1,4 @@\n-# WebView\n-\n-An embedded web browser.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/webview-cocoa.png](/reference/images/webview-cocoa.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux\n-\n-![/reference/images/webview-gtk.png](/reference/images/webview-gtk.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows\n-\n-![/reference/images/webview-winforms.png](/reference/images/webview-winforms.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android\n-\n-![/reference/images/webview-android.png](/reference/images/webview-android.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/webview-iOS.png](/reference/images/webview-iOS.png){ width=\"450\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual {{ not_supported }}\n-\n-Not supported\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"WebView\", width=450) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/widget.md b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/widget.md\nindex 2987abb756..8360fb7684 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/widget.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/widgets/widget.md\n@@ -1,11 +1,4 @@\n-# Widget\n-\n-The abstract base class of all widgets. This class should not be instantiated directly.\n-\n-Availability ([Key][api-status-key])  <!-- rumdl-disable-line MD013 -->\n-{: .availability-title }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"reference/data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"reference/data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"ComponentName\"]].isin([\"Widget\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n+{{ component_header(\"Widget\") }}\n \n ## Reference\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/window.md b/docs/en/reference/api/window.md\nindex 47c509a8bb..03aa01fa93 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/window.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/window.md\n@@ -1,78 +1,4 @@\n-# Window\n-\n-An operating system-managed container of widgets.\n-\n-/// tab | macOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/window-cocoa.png](/reference/images/window-cocoa.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Linux\n-\n-![/reference/images/window-gtk.png](/reference/images/window-gtk.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Windows\n-\n-![/reference/images/window-winforms.png](/reference/images/window-winforms.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Android\n-\n-![/reference/images/window-android.png](/reference/images/window-android.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | iOS\n-\n-![/reference/images/window-iOS.png](/reference/images/window-iOS.png){ width=\"300\" }\n-\n-/// caption\n-\n-///\n-\n-<!-- TODO: Update alt text -->\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Web\n-\n-Screenshot not available\n-\n-///\n-\n-/// tab | Textual\n-\n-Screenshot not available\n-\n-///\n+{{ component_header(\"Window\", width=300) }}\n \n ## Usage\n \ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml b/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..57238edd94\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,353 @@\n+Core application components:\n+  path: ''\n+\n+  App:\n+    description: The top-level representation of an application.\n+    display: table\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Window:\n+    description: An operating system-managed container of widgets.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  MainWindow:\n+    description: A window that can use the full set of window-level user interface elements.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  DocumentWindow:\n+    description: A window that can be used as the main interface to a document-based app.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - android\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+General widgets:\n+  path: widgets\n+\n+  ActivityIndicator:\n+    description: A small animated indicator showing activity on a task of indeterminate length, usually rendered as a \"spinner\" animation.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Button:\n+    description: A button that can be pressed or clicked.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Canvas:\n+    description: A drawing area for 2D vector graphics.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  DateInput:\n+    description: A widget to select a calendar date.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  DetailedList:\n+    description: An ordered list of content where each item has an icon, a main heading, and a line of supplementary text.\n+    beta:\n+      - winforms\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Divider:\n+    description: A separator used to visually distinguish two sections of content in a layout.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  ImageView:\n+    description: A widget that displays an image.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Label:\n+    description: A text label for annotating forms or interfaces.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  MapView:\n+    description: A zoomable map that can be annotated with location pins.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  MultilineTextInput:\n+    description: A scrollable panel that allows for the display and editing of multiple lines of text.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  NumberInput:\n+    description: A text input that is limited to numeric input.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  PasswordInput:\n+    description: A widget to allow the entry of a password. Any value typed by the user will be obscured, allowing the user to see the number of characters they have typed, but not the actual characters.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  ProgressBar:\n+    description: A horizontal bar to visualize task progress. The task being monitored can be of known or indeterminate length.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Selection:\n+    description: A widget to select a single option from a list of alternatives.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Slider:\n+    description: A widget for selecting a value within a range. The range is shown as a horizontal line, and the selected value is shown as a draggable marker.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Switch:\n+    description: 'A clickable button with two stable states: True (on, checked); and False (off, unchecked). The button has a text label.'\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Table:\n+    description: A widget for displaying columns of tabular data.\n+    beta:\n+      - android\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  TextInput:\n+    description: A widget for the display and editing of a single line of text.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+    unsupported:\n+      - gtk\n+      - textual\n+\n+  TimeInput:\n+    description: A widget to select a clock time.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+\n+  Tree:\n+    description: A widget for displaying a hierarchical tree of tabular data.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - winforms\n+      - iOS\n+      - android\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  WebView:\n+    description: An embedded web browser.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Widget:\n+    description: The abstract base class of all widgets. This class should not be be instantiated directly.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+    display: table\n+\n+Layout widgets:\n+  path: containers\n+\n+  Box:\n+    description: A generic container for other widgets. Used to construct layouts.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+    display: table\n+\n+  ScrollContainer:\n+    description: A container that can display a layout larger than the area of the container.\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+    unsupported:\n+      - textual\n+\n+  SplitContainer:\n+    description: A container that divides an area into two panels with a movable border.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - android\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  OptionContainer:\n+    description: A container that can display multiple labeled tabs of content.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+Resources:\n+  path: resources\n+\n+  App paths:\n+    description: A mechanism for obtaining platform-appropriate filesystem locations for an application.\n+    display: table\n+    path: resources/app_paths.md\n+    beta:\n+      - textual\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+\n+  Command:\n+    description: A representation of app functionality that the user can invoke from\n+      menus or toolbars.\n+    display: table\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Dialogs:\n+    description: Short-lived windows asking the user for input.\n+    display: table\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Document:\n+    description: A representation of a file on disk that will be displayed in one or more windows.\n+    display: table\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - android\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Font:\n+    description: A representation of a font.\n+    display: table\n+    path: resources/fonts.md\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Icon:\n+    description: A small, square image used to provide easily identifiable visual context to a widget.\n+    display: table\n+    path: resources/icons.md\n+    beta:\n+      - textual\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+\n+  Image:\n+    description: Graphical content of arbitrary size.\n+    display: table\n+    path: resources/images.md\n+    unsupported:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Status icons:\n+    description: Icons that appear in the system tray for representing app status\n+      while the app isn't visible.\n+    unsupported:\n+      - iOS\n+      - android\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Source:\n+    description: A base class for data source implementations.\n+    display: hide\n+    path: resources/sources/source.md\n+\n+  ListSource:\n+    description: A data source describing an ordered list of data.\n+    display: hide\n+    path: resources/sources/list_source.md\n+\n+  TreeSource:\n+    description: A data source describing an ordered hierarchical tree of data.\n+    display: hide\n+    path: resources/sources/tree_source.md\n+\n+  ValueSource:\n+    description: A data source describing a single value.\n+    display: hide\n+    path: resources/sources/value_source.md\n+\n+  Validators:\n+    description: Mechanisms for validating that input meets a given set of criteria.\n+    display: hide\n+\n+Hardware:\n+  path: hardware\n+\n+  Camera:\n+    description: A sensor that can capture photos and/or video.\n+    display: table\n+    unsupported:\n+      - gtk\n+      - winforms\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Location services:\n+    description: A sensor that can capture the geographical location of the device.\n+    display: table\n+    path: hardware/location.md\n+    unsupported:\n+      - winforms\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+  Screen:\n+    description: A representation of a screen attached to a device.\n+    display: table\n+    path: hardware/screens.md\n+    beta:\n+      - web\n+      - textual\n+\n+Other:\n+  path: ''\n+\n+  Constants:\n+    description: Symbolic constants used by various APIs.\n+    display: hide\n+\n+  Keys:\n+    description: Symbolic representation of keys used for keyboard shortcuts.\n+    display: hide\n+\n+  Types:\n+    description: Utility data structures used by Toga APIs.\n+    display: hide\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/data/widgets_by_platform.csv b/docs/en/reference/data/widgets_by_platform.csv\ndeleted file mode 100644\nindex d9964bc034..0000000000\n--- a/docs/en/reference/data/widgets_by_platform.csv\n+++ /dev/null\n@@ -1,47 +0,0 @@\n-ComponentName,Type,Component,Description,macOS,GTK,Windows,iOS,Android,Web,Terminal\n-Application,Core Component,[`App`][toga.App],The application itself,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-Window,Core Component,[`Window`][toga.Window],An operating system-managed container of widgets.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-DocumentWindow,Core Component,[`DocumentWindow`][toga.DocumentWindow],A window that can be used as the main interface to a document-based app.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,,,\n-MainWindow,Core Component,[`MainWindow`][toga.MainWindow],A window that can use the full set of window-level user interface elements.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-ActivityIndicator,General Widget,[`ActivityIndicator`][toga.ActivityIndicator],A spinning activity animation,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Button,General Widget,[`Button`][toga.Button],Basic clickable Button,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-Canvas,General Widget,[`Canvas`][toga.Canvas],A drawing area for 2D vector graphics.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-DateInput,General Widget,[`DateInput`][toga.DateInput],A widget to select a calendar date,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-DetailedList,General Widget,[`DetailedList`][toga.DetailedList],\"An ordered list of content where each item has an icon, a main heading, and a line of supplementary text.\",\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Divider,General Widget,[`Divider`][toga.Divider],A horizontal or vertical line,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-ImageView,General Widget,[`ImageView`][toga.ImageView],A widget that displays an image,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Label,General Widget,[`Label`][toga.Label],Text label,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-MapView,General Widget,[`MapView`][toga.MapView],A zoomable map that can be annotated with location pins,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-MultilineTextInput,General Widget,[`MultilineTextInput`][toga.MultilineTextInput],Multi-line Text Input field,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-NumberInput,General Widget,[`NumberInput`][toga.NumberInput],A text input that is limited to numeric input,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-PasswordInput,General Widget,[`PasswordInput`][toga.PasswordInput],A text input that hides its input,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-ProgressBar,General Widget,[`ProgressBar`][toga.ProgressBar],Progress Bar,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Selection,General Widget,[`Selection`][toga.Selection],A widget to select a single option from a list of alternatives.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Slider,General Widget,[`Slider`][toga.Slider],Slider,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Switch,General Widget,[`Switch`][toga.Switch],Switch,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Table,General Widget,[`Table`][toga.Table],A widget for displaying columns of tabular data.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\u25cb,,\n-TextInput,General Widget,[`TextInput`][toga.TextInput],A widget for the display and editing of a single line of text.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-TimeInput,General Widget,[`TimeInput`][toga.TimeInput],A widget to select a clock time,\u25cf,,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-Tree,General Widget,[`Tree`][toga.Tree],A widget for displaying a hierarchical tree of tabular data.,\u25cf,\u25cf,,,,,\n-WebView,General Widget,[`WebView`][toga.WebView],A panel for displaying HTML,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Widget,General Widget,[`Widget`][toga.Widget],The base widget,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-Box,Layout Widget,[`Box`][toga.Box],Container for components,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-ScrollContainer,Layout Widget,[`ScrollContainer`][toga.ScrollContainer],A container that can display a layout larger than the area of the container,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\n-SplitContainer,Layout Widget,[`SplitContainer`][toga.SplitContainer],A container that divides an area into two panels with a movable border,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,,,\n-OptionContainer,Layout Widget,[`OptionContainer`][toga.OptionContainer],A container that can display multiple labeled tabs of content,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Camera,Hardware,[`Camera`][toga.hardware.camera.Camera],A sensor that can capture photos and/or video.,\u25cf,,,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Location,Hardware,[`Location`][toga.hardware.location.Location],A sensor that can capture the geographical location of the device.,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Screen,Hardware,[`Screen`][toga.screens.Screen],A representation of a screen attached to a device.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-App Paths,Resource,[`Paths`][toga.paths.Paths],A mechanism for obtaining platform-appropriate filesystem locations for an application.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\u25cb\n-Command,Resource,[`Command`][toga.Command],Command,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\u25cf,,\n-Dialogs,Resource,[Dialogs][dialogs],A short-lived window asking the user for input,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cb,\u25cb\n-Document,Resource,[`Document`][toga.Document],A representation of a file on disk that will be displayed in one or more windows.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,,,\n-Font,Resource,[`Font`][toga.Font],A text font,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-Icon,Resource,[`Icon`][toga.Icon],\"A small, square image, used to provide easily identifiable visual context to a widget.\",\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\u25cb\n-Image,Resource,[`Image`][toga.Image],Graphical content of arbitrary size.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,\n-ListSource,Resource,[`ListSource`][toga.sources.ListSource],A data source describing an ordered list of data.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf\n-Source,Resource,[`Source`][toga.sources.Source],A base class for data source implementations.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf\n-StatusIcons,Resource,[Status Icons][statusicons],Icons that appear in the system tray for representing app status while the app isn't visible.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,,,,\n-TreeSource,Resource,[`TreeSource`][toga.sources.TreeSource],A data source describing an ordered hierarchical tree of data.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf\n-Validators,Resource,[Validators][validators],A mechanism for validating that input meets a given set of criteria.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf\n-ValueSource,Resource,[`ValueSource`][toga.sources.ValueSource],A data source describing a single value.,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf,\u25cf\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/dateinput-linux.png b/docs/en/reference/images/dateinput-gtk.png\nsimilarity index 100%\nrename from docs/en/reference/images/dateinput-linux.png\nrename to docs/en/reference/images/dateinput-gtk.png\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-android.png b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-android.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..29ab02cb6d\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-android.png differ\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-cocoa.png b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-cocoa.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..29ab02cb6d\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-cocoa.png differ\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-gtk.png b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-gtk.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..29ab02cb6d\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-gtk.png differ\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-iOS.png b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-iOS.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..29ab02cb6d\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-iOS.png differ\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-winforms.png b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-winforms.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..29ab02cb6d\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/imageview-winforms.png differ\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/widgets_by_platform.md b/docs/en/reference/widgets_by_platform.md\nindex fc7cd120b8..1fa017a765 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/widgets_by_platform.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/widgets_by_platform.md\n@@ -6,22 +6,15 @@\n |------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|\n | {{ fully_supported }}  | **Fully supported**                                      |\n \n-## Core Components {: .widgets_by_platform }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[2,4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"Type\"]].isin([\"Core Component\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n-\n-## General Widgets {: .widgets_by_platform }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[2,4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"Type\"]].isin([\"General Widget\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n-\n-## Layout Widgets {: .widgets_by_platform }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[2,4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"Type\"]].isin([\"Layout Widget\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n-\n-## Hardware {: .widgets_by_platform }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[2,4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"Type\"]].isin([\"Hardware\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n-\n-## Resources {: .widgets_by_platform }\n-\n-{{ pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\", na_filter=False, usecols=[2,4,5,6,7,8,9,10])[pd_read_csv(\"data/widgets_by_platform.csv\")[[\"Type\"]].isin([\"Resource\"]).all(axis=1)] | convert_to_md_table }}\n+{% for category in [\n+\t\"Core application components\",\n+\t\"General widgets\",\n+\t\"Layout widgets\",\n+\t\"Resources\",\n+\t\"Hardware\",\n+] %}\n+## {{ category }} { .widgets_by_platform }\n+\n+{{ api_table(category, platforms=True) }}\n+\n+{% endfor %}\ndiff --git a/docs/en/stylesheets/toga.css b/docs/en/stylesheets/toga.css\nindex 8d21d40d6c..c6eb58d0a2 100644\n--- a/docs/en/stylesheets/toga.css\n+++ b/docs/en/stylesheets/toga.css\n@@ -74,22 +74,22 @@\n }\n \n /* API Reference tables */\n-h2[id^=\"api-reference-\"] + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table table {\n+h2.api-reference + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table table {\n     font-size: 0.73rem;\n }\n \n-h2[id^=\"api-reference-\"] + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table table thead tr th {\n+h2.api-reference + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table th {\n     text-align: center;\n     padding: 0 0.25em;\n     background-color: light-dark(#e8e8e8, #313643);\n }\n \n-h2[id^=\"api-reference-\"] + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table table tbody tr td {\n+h2.api-reference + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table td {\n     padding: 0.2em 0.4em;\n     vertical-align: middle;\n }\n \n-h2[id^=\"api-reference-\"] + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table table tbody tr td:first-of-type {\n+h2.api-reference + .md-typeset__scrollwrap .md-typeset__table td:first-of-type {\n     border-right: .05rem solid var(--md-typeset-table-color);\n }\n \ndiff --git a/docs/main.py b/docs/main.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..15dfaa8815\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/docs/main.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,141 @@\n+# Macros module for MkDocs-Macros\n+# For more info: https://mkdocs-macros-plugin.readthedocs.io/en/latest/macros/\n+\n+from collections import defaultdict\n+from pathlib import Path\n+\n+import yaml\n+from tabulate import tabulate\n+\n+\n+def slugify(string):\n+    return string.lower().replace(\" \", \"\")\n+\n+\n+PLATFORMS_MAPPING = {\n+    \"cocoa\": \"macOS\",\n+    \"gtk\": \"GTK\",\n+    \"winforms\": \"Windows\",\n+    \"iOS\": \"iOS\",\n+    \"android\": \"Android\",\n+    \"web\": \"Web\",\n+    \"textual\": \"Terminal\",\n+}\n+\n+with Path(\"docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\").open() as file:\n+    api_data = yaml.safe_load(file)\n+\n+APIS_BY_NAME = {}\n+APIS_BY_CATEGORY = defaultdict(list)\n+\n+for category_name, category_contents in api_data.items():\n+    category_path = Path(category_contents.pop(\"path\"))\n+    for component_name, component in category_contents.items():\n+        if str_path := component.get(\"path\"):\n+            path = Path(str_path)\n+        else:\n+            path = category_path / f\"{slugify(component_name)}.md\"\n+\n+        unsupported = component.get(\"unsupported\", [])\n+        beta = component.get(\"beta\", [])\n+        for backend in unsupported + beta:\n+            if backend not in PLATFORMS_MAPPING:\n+                raise ValueError(f\"Unrecognized backend {backend}\")\n+\n+        platform_support = {\n+            platform: \"\" if backend in unsupported else \"\u25cb\" if backend in beta else \"\u25cf\"\n+            for backend, platform in PLATFORMS_MAPPING.items()\n+        }\n+\n+        api = {\n+            \"link\": f\"[{component_name}]({path})\",\n+            \"link_from_platforms\": f\"[{component_name}]({Path('api') / path})\",\n+            \"description\": component[\"description\"],\n+            \"path_from_platforms\": Path(\"api\") / path,\n+            \"platforms\": platform_support,\n+            \"display\": component.get(\"display\", \"tabs\"),\n+        }\n+\n+        APIS_BY_NAME[component_name] = api\n+        APIS_BY_CATEGORY[category_name].append(api)\n+\n+\n+def component_support(name, width, alt_file):\n+    \"\"\"Render component's support by platform, as a table or tabbed view, as needed.\"\"\"\n+    component = APIS_BY_NAME[name]\n+\n+    if component[\"display\"] == \"table\":\n+        return (\n+            \"Availability ([Key][api-status-key])\\n{: .availability-title }\\n\\n\"\n+            + tabulate([component[\"platforms\"]], headers=\"keys\", tablefmt=\"github\")\n+        )\n+    elif component[\"display\"] == \"tabs\":\n+        return component_tab_view(name, component, width, alt_file)\n+    else:\n+        return \"\"\n+\n+\n+def component_tab_view(name, component, width, alt_file):\n+    \"\"\"Render component's support by platform as a tabbed view.\"\"\"\n+    slug = alt_file if alt_file else slugify(name)\n+    tabs = []\n+    for (platform, status), backend in zip(\n+        # Zip in the keys of PLATFORM_MAPPING to have the backend name.\n+        component[\"platforms\"].items(),\n+        PLATFORMS_MAPPING,\n+        strict=True,\n+    ):\n+        status_marker = {\n+            # Full support\n+            \"\u25cf\": \"\",\n+            # Beta support (\u03b2)\n+            \"\u25cb\": \"^&beta;^\",\n+            # Not supported (\u274c)\n+            \"\": \" ^&#x274C;^\",\n+        }[status]\n+\n+        if not status:\n+            content = \"Not supported\"\n+        else:\n+            file_name = f\"{slug}-{backend}.png\"\n+            if Path(f\"docs/en/reference/images/{file_name}\").is_file():\n+                content = (\n+                    f\"![{name} on {platform}](/reference/images/{file_name})\"\n+                    f'{{ width=\"{width}\" }}\\n\\n'\n+                    \"/// caption\\n\\n///\\n\\n\"\n+                )\n+            else:\n+                content = \"Screenshot not available\"\n+\n+        tabs.append(f\"/// tab | {platform}{status_marker}\\n\\n{content}\\n\\n///\")\n+\n+    return \"\\n\\n\".join(tabs)\n+\n+\n+def define_env(env):\n+    @env.macro\n+    def api_table(category, platforms=False):\n+        \"\"\"Render table of a category of APIs for the two reference pages.\"\"\"\n+        components = APIS_BY_CATEGORY[category]\n+        rows = [\n+            {\"Component\": component[\"link_from_platforms\"], **component[\"platforms\"]}\n+            if platforms\n+            else {\n+                \"Component\": component[\"link\"],\n+                \"Description\": component[\"description\"],\n+            }\n+            for component in components\n+        ]\n+        return tabulate(rows, headers=\"keys\", tablefmt=\"github\")\n+\n+    @env.macro\n+    def component_header(name, width=None, alt_file=None):\n+        \"\"\"Render top of component page: title, description, and platform support.\"\"\"\n+        component = APIS_BY_NAME[name]\n+        return \"\\n\\n\".join(\n+            [\n+                f\"# {name}\",\n+                component[\"description\"],\n+                component_support(name, width=width, alt_file=alt_file),\n+            ]\n+        )\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex 215041f550..dcf3851edc 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -133,6 +133,7 @@ dev = [\n # and the docs contribution guide.\n docs = [\n     \"beeware-docs-tools @ git+https://github.com/beeware/beeware-docs-tools\",\n-    \"mkdocs-table-reader-plugin==3.1.0\",\n     \"setuptools-scm==9.2.0\",\n+    \"tabulate==0.9.0\",\n+    \"PyYAML==6.0.3\"\n ]\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\"APIs by Platform\" page links different than \"API Reference\"\n### What is the problem or limitation you are having?\n\nOn the API Reference page, the names are all rendered as normal text, and link to the top of the relevant page:\n\n<img width=\"858\" height=\"252\" alt=\"API Reference\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f4dfe606-8d9c-4832-87a6-a824decf2aef\" />\n\nHowever, on Toga APIs by Platform, most of the links are the code-formatted class name, and link not to the page itself, but to the cross-reference anchor for the class itself... except for concepts *aren't* primarily one specific class, which instead are rendered in normal text and link to the top of their page.\n\n<img width=\"842\" height=\"249\" alt=\"APIs by Platform\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a482ea1d-b069-4ceb-b2f4-874c9faee8ee\" />\n\nIt's not only inconsistent with the other page, it's inconsistent with itself.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like\n\nI think it would make more sense for the chart on APIs by Platform to match the form of that on API Reference: normal text, and links to the pages rather than class anchors.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered\n\nIt could also make a lot of sense to simply fold the platform support information *into* the main API reference page... if a way could be devised to do that without space becoming incredibly cramped.\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_\n", "hints_text": "Agreed we should avoid the inconsistency; page headings rather than class anchors definitely makes sense to me as the preferred form.\n\nAs for the bigger idea - I agree it would be good to get platform support info onto the API page... but space constraints will definitely make that difficult.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Agreed we should avoid the inconsistency; page headings rather than class anchors definitely makes sense to me as the preferred form.\n\nAs for the bigger idea - I agree it would be good to get platform support info onto the API page... but space constraints will definitely make that difficult.\n\n> As for the bigger idea - I agree it would be good to get platform support info onto the API page... but space constraints will definitely make that difficult.\n\nMy 2 cents -- we're already maintaining a screenshot tab structure with support info, like the beta, not supported, and supported icons.  However as I've caught in https://github.com/beeware/toga/pull/3769/files#diff-8eaa351aec47a3e86f97a0f3c2470bf01b5a27550dc8c4ff70a6ecda2c90646fL17-R27 the support table isn't always kept up-to-date; DateInput on GTK has support but it's shown as not doing so.\nThose are both good points... a tab on the API page to switch between descriptions and platform support doesn't sound unreasonable. I'll try mocking it up and see how it looks.\n\nAs to things getting out of sync: nonvisual components like App, Box, etc., pull their support grid from the same CSV page the overall chart does. Tabbed views are currently just hard-coded. I'm already working on a PR to streamline and centralize this sort of info; I should probably be able to tie the tab views into that as well. (Perhaps a supported platform of a visual widget that doesn't yet have a screenshot should even throw a linting error.)\n@HalfWhitt Sorry, I didn't mean a tab to switch between descriptions and platform support, I meant that the platform support info is already on the screneshot tabs.\n\nRegarding your streamlining PR: AFAICT #3769 is getting close to merge, perhaps 1-2 weeks.  Just a headsup on conflicts becaue #3769 has massive changes adding ,11 to the column filters and also adding a Qt tab and renaming the Linux tab to Linux (GTK).\n> Regarding your streamlining PR: AFAICT [#3769](https://github.com/beeware/toga/pull/3769) is getting close to merge, perhaps 1-2 weeks. Just a headsup on conflicts becaue [#3769](https://github.com/beeware/toga/pull/3769) has massive changes adding ,11 to the column filters and also adding a Qt tab and renaming the Linux tab to Linux (GTK).\n\nThanks for the heads up \u2014 I expect I should be done before then (which, I know, are often famous last words). But despite merge conflicts, my changes might actually make yours easier, since they wouldn't have to be done in as many places.\n\n@HalfWhitt You're welcome.  Now I'm crying about the wasted minutes trying to fix various other inconsistencies in the tabs as I went...\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/96f049041a701afd100458ab576eef0c907f5863", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/81e9a8a238197ec29a9b524c083a35f4e0cb7126", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/3428181a63694d2c5bb4358f2f2e8e656c7a76af", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/c71c84f761be702a0e79f88fd5a0d2a2b5c396dc", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/43354f2a3f018cd9dd02ca741ff4a09a5a76b400", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/1ca75ad1ae8cd4c4acf3e4d8df30e0483a584f37", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/66a595a4d0a8727b5dc4b152dcb0dba17d14176e", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/085db92288119a3df08e94651bccdcf711e028f5", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/2bcf6135dbee1f50ed018b2352103619b729297e", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/901039dcc5eaeac1ece92bd268b4e0dacfa6d725"], "created_at": "2025-10-22T01:49:59Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4092, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4092", "issue_numbers": [3975], "base_commit": "9343e1fc10e951c419571f79b0248b49e347e952", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/3975.misc.md b/changes/3975.misc.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..3f8c42335b\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/3975.misc.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+The unused AUTHORS file has been removed from the toga-demo package.\ndiff --git a/demo/AUTHORS b/demo/AUTHORS\ndeleted file mode 100755\nindex 085bf109f3..0000000000\n--- a/demo/AUTHORS\n+++ /dev/null\n@@ -1,8 +0,0 @@\n-Toga Demo was originally created in July 2014.\n-\n-The PRIMARY AUTHORS are (and/or have been):\n-    Russell Keith-Magee\n-\n-And here is an inevitably incomplete list of MUCH-APPRECIATED CONTRIBUTORS --\n-people who have submitted patches, reported bugs, added translations, helped\n-answer newbie questions, and generally made Toga Demo that much better:\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Get Rid of toga/demo/AUTHORS\n### What is the problem or limitation you are having?\n\nI found this file toga/demo/AUTHORS by accident while fooling around.  I noticed that it has not been changed to include any significant contributors, and it has little utility since the main toga repo nor the backends have such a file.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like\n\nGet rid of it.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered\n\nEquip every backend/subpackage etc. with an equivalent file, using git history tools and/or GitHub API to query significant bug-reporters and contributors, and keep keeping them up to date.\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_\n", "hints_text": "Hi!\nI\u2019m relatively new to the open-source world and I\u2019m starting to make my first contributions. I wanted to ask whether it would be okay for me to work on this issue.\n\nAlso, if possible, could you explain what qualities make bug reporters and contributors significant to the project?\n[I am not on the core team.]\n\nNote that some of the core team is on holiday break and may take up to 8 days to respond.\n@ABolouk Absolutely and welcome to BeeWare!  Posting a comment here and starting work on it in the form of a PR is enough.  There are information on how to contribute [here](https://toga.beeware.org/en/latest/how-to/contribute/) -- Note, that is the *latest* version, not the *stable* version (pick the version in the right down corner on Read the Docs) which includes an expanded contribution guide. \n\nThere's https://toga.beeware.org/en/latest/how-to/contribute/first-time-contributors/#every-contribution-matters on how contributions can be significant, especially for first timers.\n> Hi! I\u2019m relatively new to the open-source world and I\u2019m starting to make my first contributions. I wanted to ask whether it would be okay for me to work on this issue.\n\nHi! I *am* a member of the core team - as John noted, you're welcome to take on this issue if you want - we don't have a formal \"assignment\" process for user contributions.\n\nIf you need any pointers on how to get started beyond what is in the contribution guide, let us know - we're happy to help.\n\n> Also, if possible, could you explain what qualities make bug reporters and contributors significant to the project?\n\nThat's a complicated question; the simplest answer I can give is \"persistence\". \n\nAll contributions are valuable; but having someone who turns up and *keeps* turning up is the single most useful property they can have. A once-off contribution can be reviewed; but when the same user contributes a second time, and a third, and a fourth, we can get to know *them* and their contribution style. We learn what areas of expertise they have, and what sort of bugs they're prone to. That makes the reviewing process easier, because we know where we have to pay special attention. \n\nIt also means they've demonstrated that they're likely to stick around, so they're a candidate for giving other responsibilities in the project. For example, if someone hangs around for six months of regular contribution, and they're producing high quality work demonstrating they have particular expertise in an area of the code, we might ask them to join the core team, or give them some other key responsibility (such as responsibility for regular maintenance work that needs to be performed). \n\n", "all_hints_text": "Hi!\nI\u2019m relatively new to the open-source world and I\u2019m starting to make my first contributions. I wanted to ask whether it would be okay for me to work on this issue.\n\nAlso, if possible, could you explain what qualities make bug reporters and contributors significant to the project?\n[I am not on the core team.]\n\nNote that some of the core team is on holiday break and may take up to 8 days to respond.\n@ABolouk Absolutely and welcome to BeeWare!  Posting a comment here and starting work on it in the form of a PR is enough.  There are information on how to contribute [here](https://toga.beeware.org/en/latest/how-to/contribute/) -- Note, that is the *latest* version, not the *stable* version (pick the version in the right down corner on Read the Docs) which includes an expanded contribution guide. \n\nThere's https://toga.beeware.org/en/latest/how-to/contribute/first-time-contributors/#every-contribution-matters on how contributions can be significant, especially for first timers.\n> Hi! I\u2019m relatively new to the open-source world and I\u2019m starting to make my first contributions. I wanted to ask whether it would be okay for me to work on this issue.\n\nHi! I *am* a member of the core team - as John noted, you're welcome to take on this issue if you want - we don't have a formal \"assignment\" process for user contributions.\n\nIf you need any pointers on how to get started beyond what is in the contribution guide, let us know - we're happy to help.\n\n> Also, if possible, could you explain what qualities make bug reporters and contributors significant to the project?\n\nThat's a complicated question; the simplest answer I can give is \"persistence\". \n\nAll contributions are valuable; but having someone who turns up and *keeps* turning up is the single most useful property they can have. A once-off contribution can be reviewed; but when the same user contributes a second time, and a third, and a fourth, we can get to know *them* and their contribution style. We learn what areas of expertise they have, and what sort of bugs they're prone to. That makes the reviewing process easier, because we know where we have to pay special attention. \n\nIt also means they've demonstrated that they're likely to stick around, so they're a candidate for giving other responsibilities in the project. For example, if someone hangs around for six months of regular contribution, and they're producing high quality work demonstrating they have particular expertise in an area of the code, we might ask them to join the core team, or give them some other key responsibility (such as responsibility for regular maintenance work that needs to be performed). \nHi @freakboy3742 I have raised the PR Kindly review it and let me know for any changes thanks!!\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/925f77b492c22adf7b9ebf2b9b71e0ba81f6252d", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/dfa9476e0e999ca1279c916de9447d6221d30bd0"], "created_at": "2026-01-18T17:18:50Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 3985, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-3985", "issue_numbers": [3984], "base_commit": "6b59fc7d3c74ad8d7d41c15a881c96677c735156", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/3984.bugfix.md b/changes/3984.bugfix.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..78bb760760\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/3984.bugfix.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+Apps now log an error instead of crashing if the system locale value is set to an unknown or invalid value.\ndiff --git a/core/src/toga/app.py b/core/src/toga/app.py\nindex a6e4ee86c1..90d0c494ff 100644\n--- a/core/src/toga/app.py\n+++ b/core/src/toga/app.py\n@@ -3,6 +3,7 @@\n import asyncio\n import importlib.metadata\n import locale\n+import os\n import signal\n import sys\n import warnings\n@@ -202,7 +203,14 @@ def __init__(\n             app can manage.\n         \"\"\"\n         # Sets Python's locale settings to the language settings of the system.\n-        locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, \"\")\n+        # If the local is unknown (e.g. en-FR), catch the error, log and ignore,\n+        # as there's not much else we can do.\n+        try:\n+            locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, \"\")\n+        except locale.Error:  # pragma: no cover\n+            print(\n+                f\"Unable to set locale to match system value of {os.getenv('LANG')!r}\"\n+            )\n \n         # Initialize empty widgets registry\n         self._widgets = WidgetRegistry()\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Unknown locales crash app at startup\n### Describe the bug\n\nIf your system has a locale set to something unknown or invalid, a Toga app will crash at startup\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a hello world app\n2. Export an environment variable of `LANG=en_FR.UTF-8`\n3. See error\n\n```\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<frozen runpy>\", line 198, in _run_module_as_main\n  File \"<frozen runpy>\", line 88, in _run_code\n  File \"/Users/rkm/beeware/toga/examples/tutorial0/tutorial/__main__.py\", line 4, in <module>\n    main().main_loop()\n    ^^^^^^\n  File \"/Users/rkm/beeware/toga/examples/tutorial0/tutorial/app.py\", line 20, in main\n    return toga.App(\"First App\", \"org.beeware.toga.examples.tutorial\", startup=build)\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n  File \"/Users/rkm/beeware/toga/core/src/toga/app.py\", line 208, in __init__\n    locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, \"\")\n  File \"/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.12/lib/python3.12/locale.py\", line 615, in setlocale\n    return _setlocale(category, locale)\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\nlocale.Error: unsupported locale setting\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nApp shouldn't crash with an unknown locale. \n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: macOS 15.6.1, iOS 18.6\n- Python version: 3.14\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: 0.5.3\n\n\n### Logs\n\n```\n\n```\n\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis was introduced in #3870 as a fix for decimal handling; but the edge case of unknown/invalid locales wasn't handled. \n\nIt can be generated on iOS by setting the language to English and Region to France.\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/480ec8c7f431d782128b0a71e98f726608c6bb6e"], "created_at": "2025-12-14T22:42:01Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 3999, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-3999", "issue_numbers": [3998], "base_commit": "916f7d79e9829b0ab189def0a13950512f81a767", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/3998.bugfix.md b/changes/3998.bugfix.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..b66cbe71bb\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/3998.bugfix.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+NumberInput values on macOS no longer visually disappear when the widget loses focus.\ndiff --git a/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/numberinput.py b/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/numberinput.py\nindex 64b956e884..6a2316d2a0 100644\n--- a/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/numberinput.py\n+++ b/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/numberinput.py\n@@ -21,6 +21,8 @@\n     NSTextFieldSquareBezel,\n     NSTextView,\n     NSView,\n+    c_void_p,\n+    send_super,\n )\n \n from .base import Widget\n@@ -59,6 +61,13 @@ def textDidEndEditing_(self, notification) -> None:\n         # Loss of focus; ensure that the displayed value\n         # matches the clipped, normalized decimal value\n         self.impl.set_value(self.interface.value)\n+        send_super(\n+            __class__,\n+            self,\n+            \"textDidEndEditing:\",\n+            notification,\n+            argtypes=[c_void_p],\n+        )\n \n \n class NumberInput(Widget):\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "NumberInput value visually disappears on blur (macOS)\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen a `NumberInput` field loses focus (blur), the displayed value visually disappears. The value is still present internally (can be read via `widget.value`), but the text field appears blank until you click on it again.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Run the attached `test_numberinput.py` code\n2. Click on the NumberInput field (shows \"5.0\")\n3. Click on the TextInput field below it\n4. Observe: The NumberInput now appears blank\n\n```python\n\"\"\"\nNumberInput value disappears on blur (macOS).\n\nSteps:\n1. Click on the NumberInput\n2. Click on the TextInput\n3. NumberInput value visually disappears\n\"\"\"\n\nimport toga\nfrom toga.style import Pack\nfrom toga.style.pack import COLUMN\n\n\nclass MinimalApp(toga.App):\n    def startup(self):\n        box = toga.Box(style=Pack(direction=COLUMN, margin=20))\n\n        self.number = toga.NumberInput(min=1, max=10, step=0.5, value=5)\n        box.add(self.number)\n\n        self.text = toga.TextInput(value=\"Click here after clicking number field\")\n        box.add(self.text)\n\n        self.main_window = toga.MainWindow(title=\"NumberInput Bug\")\n        self.main_window.content = box\n        self.main_window.show()\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    MinimalApp(\"Test\", \"com.test\").main_loop()\n``` \n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe NumberInput should continue displaying its value (\"5.0\") after losing focus.\n\n### Screenshots\n\nApp open:\n<img width=\"671\" height=\"521\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f219f4e8-608e-4e62-a340-bb21cc03c7fb\" />\n\nAfter clicking away from the number field:\n<img width=\"681\" height=\"525\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4c5d3c9e-059c-43dd-8282-698220ef6a8d\" />\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: macOS 26.2 (Build 25C56)\n- Python version: 3.13\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: 0.5.3\n\n\n### Logs\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\n- The value is still correct internally - `widget.value` returns the expected value\n- This appears to be a display/redraw issue in the Cocoa backend\n- The issue occurs on blur regardless of whether the value was modified\n- Clicking back on the NumberInput restores the visual display\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Hello @paulscan! Thanks for the bug report and associated PR! As was indicated, most of the core team is on holiday leave. We'll be checking in weekly, so that's the longest it'll be before you get a response. We appreciate your patience.\nThanks for the report; this appears to be a Liquid Glass/macOS 26 issue; I can't reproduce it on macOS 16.\n> Thanks for the report; this appears to be a Liquid Glass/macOS 26 issue; I can't reproduce it on macOS 16.\n\nNote that it appears that the user\u2019s app is running with legacy design with an old macOS compiled Python interpreter\u2026 so it\u2019s not necessarily the design language itself, but logic changes in new macOS.\n\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/671fd0ea518912ac006fe4b98b90f06187ef3d06", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/838cccf26b8ff10265000552e42139c34f9338b7", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f8ad4272c0750136e04950051f5cf5af177a67bb"], "created_at": "2025-12-21T01:39:14Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4011, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4011", "issue_numbers": [4005], "base_commit": "08d01622952ed39ae358b06f144ebfb3e9a62bc8", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/4005.misc.md b/changes/4005.misc.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..4aecf734d7\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/4005.misc.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+The calculation of image divergence in Canvas tests has been improved, and the threshold for difference has been tightened.\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py\nindex 2999998a4d..c4962e61f9 100644\n--- a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py\n+++ b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py\n@@ -1,10 +1,11 @@\n import math\n import os\n+from itertools import chain\n from math import pi, radians\n from unittest.mock import Mock, call\n \n import pytest\n-from PIL import Image\n+from PIL import Image, ImageChops\n \n import toga\n from toga import Font\n@@ -106,10 +107,6 @@ async def canvas(widget, probe, on_resize_handler):\n     return widget\n \n \n-def assert_pixel(image, x, y, color):\n-    assert image.getpixel((x, y)) == color\n-\n-\n test_cleanup = build_cleanup_test(toga.Canvas, xfail_platforms=(\"android\",))\n \n \n@@ -244,7 +241,7 @@ async def test_image_data(canvas, probe):\n     )\n \n \n-def assert_reference(probe, reference, threshold=0.0):\n+def assert_reference(probe, reference, threshold=0.01):\n     \"\"\"Assert that the canvas currently matches a reference image, within an\n     RMS threshold\"\"\"\n     # Get the canvas image.\n@@ -263,21 +260,17 @@ def save():\n         image.save(save_dir / f\"{reference_variant}-full.png\")\n \n     # If a reference image exists, scale the image to the same size as the reference,\n-    # and do an MSE comparison on every pixel in 0-1 RGBA colorspace.\n+    # and do an MSE comparison on every pixel in 0-1 RGBa (premultiplied) colorspace.\n     if path.exists():\n         reference_image = Image.open(path)\n \n-        total = 0.0\n-        for y in range(reference_image.size[1]):\n-            for x in range(reference_image.size[0]):\n-                actual = scaled_image.getpixel((x, y))\n-                expected = reference_image.getpixel((x, y))\n-\n-                for act, exp in zip(actual, expected, strict=False):\n-                    err = (act / 255) - (exp / 255)\n-                    total += err * err\n+        difference = ImageChops.difference(\n+            scaled_image.convert(\"RGBa\"),\n+            reference_image.convert(\"RGBa\"),\n+        ).getdata()\n \n-        rmse = math.sqrt(total / (reference_image.size[0] * reference_image.size[1]))\n+        total_error = sum((diff / 255) ** 2 for diff in chain.from_iterable(difference))\n+        rmse = math.sqrt(total_error / 160_000)  # 200w * 200h * 4 bands\n         # If the delta exceeds threshold, save the test image and fail the test.\n         if rmse > threshold:\n             save()\n@@ -301,13 +294,7 @@ async def test_transparency(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.fill(color=rgb(0x33, 0x66, 0x99, 0.5))\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Image with transparent content and background\")\n-    # 0.1 is a big threshold; it's equivalent to 400 pixels being 100% the wrong color.\n-    # This occurs because pixel aliasing around the edge of the squares generates\n-    # different colors due to image scaling and alpha blending differences on each\n-    # platform. You could also generate 0.1 threshold error by moving the entire image 1\n-    # px to the left. However, it's difficult to find a measure that passes the edge\n-    # issue without also passing a translation error.\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"transparency\", threshold=0.1)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"transparency\")\n \n \n async def test_paths(canvas, probe):\n@@ -352,7 +339,7 @@ async def test_paths(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Pair of triangles and a black line should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"paths\", threshold=0.04)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"paths\", threshold=0.02)\n \n \n async def test_bezier_curve(canvas, probe):\n@@ -369,7 +356,7 @@ async def test_bezier_curve(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Heart should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"bezier_curve\", threshold=0.05)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"bezier_curve\", threshold=0.03)\n \n \n async def test_quadratic_curve(canvas, probe):\n@@ -386,7 +373,7 @@ async def test_quadratic_curve(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Quote bubble should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"quadratic_curve\", threshold=0.05)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"quadratic_curve\", threshold=0.03)\n \n \n async def test_arc(canvas, probe):\n@@ -425,7 +412,7 @@ async def test_arc(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Smiley face should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"arc\", threshold=0.06)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"arc\", threshold=0.03)\n \n \n async def test_ellipse(canvas, probe):\n@@ -468,7 +455,7 @@ async def test_ellipse(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke(color=GOLDENROD)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Atom should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"ellipse\", threshold=0.04)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"ellipse\", threshold=0.02)\n \n \n async def test_ellipse_path(canvas, probe):\n@@ -505,7 +492,7 @@ async def test_ellipse_path(canvas, probe):\n     context.stroke(CORNFLOWERBLUE)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Broken ellipse with connected lines should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"ellipse_path\", threshold=0.04)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"ellipse_path\", threshold=0.02)\n \n \n async def test_rect(canvas, probe):\n@@ -517,7 +504,7 @@ async def test_rect(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.fill(color=REBECCAPURPLE)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Filled rectangle should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"rect\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"rect\")\n \n \n async def test_fill(canvas, probe):\n@@ -541,7 +528,7 @@ async def test_fill(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.fill(color=CORNFLOWERBLUE, fill_rule=FillRule.EVENODD)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Stars should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"fill\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"fill\")\n \n \n async def test_stroke(canvas, probe):\n@@ -565,7 +552,7 @@ async def test_stroke(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke(color=CORNFLOWERBLUE)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Stroke should be drawn\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke\")\n \n \n async def test_stroke_and_fill(canvas, probe):\n@@ -591,8 +578,7 @@ async def test_stroke_and_fill(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke(color=REBECCAPURPLE)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Stroke should be drawn\")\n-    # TODO: Check threshold after #4011\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_and_fill\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_and_fill\")\n \n \n async def test_closed_path_context(canvas, probe):\n@@ -608,7 +594,7 @@ async def test_closed_path_context(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.stroke(color=REBECCAPURPLE, line_width=5, line_dash=[20, 30])\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Closed path should be drawn with context\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"closed_path_context\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"closed_path_context\")\n \n \n async def test_fill_context(canvas, probe):\n@@ -621,7 +607,7 @@ async def test_fill_context(canvas, probe):\n         path.line_to(x=100, y=180)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Fill should be drawn with context\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"fill_context\", threshold=0.01)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"fill_context\")\n \n \n async def test_stroke_context(canvas, probe):\n@@ -637,7 +623,7 @@ async def test_stroke_context(canvas, probe):\n         stroke.line_to(x=120, y=180)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Stroke should be drawn with context\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_context\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_context\")\n \n \n async def test_stroke_and_fill_context(canvas, probe):\n@@ -653,8 +639,7 @@ async def test_stroke_and_fill_context(canvas, probe):\n             path.line_to(x=100, y=180)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Stroke and Fill should be drawn with context\")\n-    # TODO: Check threshold after #4011\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_and_fill_context\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"stroke_and_fill_context\")\n \n \n async def test_transforms(canvas, probe):\n@@ -686,7 +671,7 @@ async def test_transforms(canvas, probe):\n     canvas.context.fill()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Transforms can be applied\")\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"transforms\", threshold=0.02)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"transforms\")\n \n \n @pytest.mark.xfail(\n@@ -763,11 +748,13 @@ async def test_write_text(canvas, probe):\n             )\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Text should be drawn\")\n-    # 0.07 is quite a high error threshold; it's equivalent to 196 pixels being\n-    # 100% the wrong color. However, fonts are the worst case for evaluating with\n-    # RMSE, as they are 100% edges; and due to minor font rendering discrepancies\n-    # and antialiasing introduced by image scaling, edges are the source of error.\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"write_text\", threshold=0.07)\n+    # 0.035 is equivalent to 49 pixels out of 4,000 being 100% the wrong color\n+    # (in premultiplied RGBa space). However, fonts are the worst case for evaluating\n+    # with RMSE, as they are 100% edges; and due to minor font rendering discrepancies\n+    # and antialiasing introduced by image scaling, edges are the source of error. Of\n+    # note, though: Gtk on Wayland is the only backend that needs it set this high.\n+    # Everything else falls below 0.02.\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"write_text\", threshold=0.035)\n \n \n @pytest.mark.xfail(\n@@ -835,11 +822,7 @@ def caption(baseline):\n             text_filler.write_text(text, left, y, font, baseline)\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Multiple text blocks should be drawn\")\n-    # 0.09 is quite a high error threshold; it's equivalent to 324 pixels being\n-    # 100% the wrong color. However, fonts are the worst case for evaluating with\n-    # RMSE, as they are 100% edges; and due to minor font rendering discrepancies\n-    # and antialiasing introduced by image scaling, edges are the source of error.\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"multiline_text\", threshold=0.09)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"multiline_text\")\n \n \n @pytest.mark.xfail(\n@@ -893,5 +876,4 @@ async def test_write_text_and_path(canvas, probe):\n         fill.begin_path()\n \n     await probe.redraw(\"Text and path should be drawn independently\")\n-    # TODO: Check threshold after #4011\n-    assert_reference(probe, \"write_text_and_path\", threshold=0.08)\n+    assert_reference(probe, \"write_text_and_path\", 0.04)\n", "problem_statement": "Canvas Image Comparison RMSE Calculation Incorrect\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen comparing the out put of Canvas operations against reference images in `assert_reference`, the error computed by summing the squared error in each *channel* in each pixel, but the mean is computed by dividing only by the number of *pixels*: https://github.com/beeware/toga/blob/5149c6f6c8c646633eeb878f2758eb9d2cb9414f/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py#L269-L279\n\nThis is a minor issue, but it had me confused for a little bit as I couldn't work out why the reported errors were so high. It means that for an RGBA image, the reported error is roughly twice what it should be.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nForce a failure in a test in testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py that is using a reference image (eg. by replacing the reference image by a different one). Observe the reported RMSE in the failure.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe correct RMSE should be:\n``` python\nrmse = math.sqrt(total / (reference_image.size[0] * reference_image.size[1] * len(reference_image.getbands()))\n```\nor something similar.\n\nIf this correction is made then the thresholds of the various tests should be lowered by the appropriate factor (either 0.5 for a 4 channel image, or ~0.57735 (= sqrt(1/3)) for a 3 channel.\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: All\n- Python version: All\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: current GitHub main\n\n\n### Logs\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis may allow the removal of comments like this in the tests:\nhttps://github.com/beeware/toga/blob/5149c6f6c8c646633eeb878f2758eb9d2cb9414f/testbed/tests/widgets/test_canvas.py#L711-L714\n\nAs currently being computed, an error of 0.07 in a 200x200 RGBA image is 196 pixel *channels* being wrong, which is actually only a difference of 49 pixels completely wrong in an RGBA image, or ~65 pixels being completely wrong in an RGB image, which is a lot better in terms of performance.\n\nAnother factor which might be worth considering is comparing images with premultiplied alpha, because non-premultiplied RGBA values of (255, 255, 255, 0) and (0, 0, 0, 0) are both completely transparent, but would be counted as different in the comparison.  This may not be a significant issue in practice, however.\n", "hints_text": "Can confirm that the math seems wrong here.  Feel free to make a PR.\nThe core team is also on holiday break and may not respond until up to 8 days later.\nThe statistical math is outside my wheelhouse... but on the subject of using a PIL image, I don't think we need to iterate separately through x and y. [Image.getdata()](https://hugovk-pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/reference/Image.html#PIL.Image.Image.getdata) returns one \"flat\" iterable sequence of all of an image's pixels. So we should be able to do something roughly along the lines of:\n\n```python\nfor actual, expected in zip(scaled_image.getdata(), reference_image.getdata()):\n```\n\nSidenote: there's a nearby `assert_pixel` function doesn't seem to be used for anything at all.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Can confirm that the math seems wrong here.  Feel free to make a PR.\nThe core team is also on holiday break and may not respond until up to 8 days later.\nThe statistical math is outside my wheelhouse... but on the subject of using a PIL image, I don't think we need to iterate separately through x and y. [Image.getdata()](https://hugovk-pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/reference/Image.html#PIL.Image.Image.getdata) returns one \"flat\" iterable sequence of all of an image's pixels. So we should be able to do something roughly along the lines of:\n\n```python\nfor actual, expected in zip(scaled_image.getdata(), reference_image.getdata()):\n```\n\nSidenote: there's a nearby `assert_pixel` function doesn't seem to be used for anything at all.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/fcc6e29c924929004e188a969e981902bfbd87fd", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/965e7b1e78151657f393f9ce915b2aaa2c9a33d7", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/a7080283ae17f4992bff1d8f85cd6f84bc14bccd", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/419af44f32c11f0c3daedc97500b3262e961c26a", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/43238689a75a136bdb8199ca27e28aebb2daac51", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/8a2e5bb1e23d11e729dda76d8a218b89ad711cea", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/d292ceba0cfe4491cf54b1b94a90f6f7c1dee150", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/890a9fa6a5d13ed9cb6e06e5a74e8a22862a7721", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/074c6b633f1995bfb6c8cb1a4b635a8bb5fc72c8"], "created_at": "2025-12-24T07:15:51Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 3992, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-3992", "issue_numbers": [4007], "base_commit": "08d01622952ed39ae358b06f144ebfb3e9a62bc8", "patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/ci.yml b/.github/workflows/ci.yml\nindex 2eb74c77d7..d4f8368229 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/ci.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/ci.yml\n@@ -367,7 +367,7 @@ jobs:\n             sleep 1\n           briefcase-run-prefix: 'DISPLAY=:99'\n           setup-python: false  # Use the system Python packages\n-          app-user-data-path: \"$HOME/.local/share/testbed\"\n+          app-user-data-path: \"$HOME/.local/share/testbed-qt\"\n \n         - backend: \"linux-wayland-qt\"\n           platform: \"linux\"\n@@ -397,7 +397,7 @@ jobs:\n             sleep 1\n           briefcase-run-prefix: \"WAYLAND_DISPLAY=toga\"\n           setup-python: false  # Use the system Python packages\n-          app-user-data-path: \"$HOME/.local/share/testbed\"\n+          app-user-data-path: \"$HOME/.local/share/testbed-qt\"\n \n         - backend: \"textual-linux\"\n           platform: \"linux\"\ndiff --git a/changes/3914.feature.11.md b/changes/3914.feature.11.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..d9c3379bee\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/3914.feature.11.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+The Canvas widget is now supported in the Qt backend.\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml b/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\nindex 807613aedb..92783d5f86 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/data/apis_by_platform.yaml\n@@ -49,7 +49,6 @@ General widgets:\n     unsupported:\n       - web\n       - textual\n-      - qt\n \n   DateInput:\n     description: A widget to select a calendar date.\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/images/canvas-qt.png b/docs/en/reference/images/canvas-qt.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..b4c08b6b98\nBinary files /dev/null and b/docs/en/reference/images/canvas-qt.png differ\ndiff --git a/qt/src/toga_qt/factory.py b/qt/src/toga_qt/factory.py\nindex bf1a936149..f6b748ef61 100644\n--- a/qt/src/toga_qt/factory.py\n+++ b/qt/src/toga_qt/factory.py\n@@ -14,6 +14,7 @@\n     from .widgets.activityindicator import ActivityIndicator\n     from .widgets.box import Box\n     from .widgets.button import Button\n+    from .widgets.canvas import Canvas\n     from .widgets.dateinput import DateInput\n     from .widgets.imageview import ImageView\n     from .widgets.label import Label\n@@ -48,6 +49,7 @@\n     \"MainWindow\",\n     \"Command\",\n     \"Button\",\n+    \"Canvas\",\n     \"DateInput\",\n     \"Font\",\n     \"Container\",\ndiff --git a/qt/src/toga_qt/fonts.py b/qt/src/toga_qt/fonts.py\nindex 0d8f0fb4c4..61c6e31a01 100644\n--- a/qt/src/toga_qt/fonts.py\n+++ b/qt/src/toga_qt/fonts.py\n@@ -120,7 +120,7 @@ def _assign_native(self, font):\n         if self.interface.variant == SMALL_CAPS:\n             font.setCapitalization(QFont.Capitalization.SmallCaps)\n         if self.interface.size != SYSTEM_DEFAULT_FONT_SIZE:\n-            font.setPointSize(self.interface.size)\n+            font.setPointSizeF(self.interface.size)\n \n         # Set the native font and remember it\n         self.native = font\ndiff --git a/qt/src/toga_qt/widgets/canvas.py b/qt/src/toga_qt/widgets/canvas.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..fb5be177b6\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/qt/src/toga_qt/widgets/canvas.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,350 @@\n+import logging\n+from math import ceil, cos, degrees, sin\n+\n+from PySide6.QtCore import QBuffer, QIODevice, QPointF, Qt\n+from PySide6.QtGui import (\n+    QFontMetrics,\n+    QMouseEvent,\n+    QPainter,\n+    QPainterPath,\n+    QPaintEvent,\n+    QPen,\n+    QTransform,\n+)\n+from PySide6.QtWidgets import QWidget\n+from travertino.size import at_least\n+\n+from toga.constants import Baseline, FillRule\n+from toga.widgets.canvas.geometry import arc_to_bezier, sweepangle\n+\n+from ..colors import native_color\n+from .base import Widget\n+\n+logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n+\n+\n+class TogaCanvas(QWidget):\n+    def __init__(self, interface, impl):\n+        super().__init__()\n+        self.interface = interface\n+        self.impl = impl\n+\n+    def paintEvent(self, event: QPaintEvent):\n+        painter = QPainter(self)\n+        try:\n+            painter.setRenderHint(QPainter.RenderHint.Antialiasing)\n+            self.impl.begin_path(painter)\n+            self.interface.context._draw(self.impl, draw_context=painter)\n+        except Exception:  # pragma: no cover\n+            logger.exception(\"Error rendering Canvas.\")\n+        finally:\n+            # we may have saved states that need to be unwound\n+            # shouldn't happen normally, but can if there is an exception\n+            # or if there is a bug where number of saves != number of restores\n+            painter.end()\n+\n+    def mousePressEvent(self, event: QMouseEvent) -> None:\n+        button = event.button()\n+        match button:\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton:\n+                self.interface.on_press(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.RightButton:\n+                self.interface.on_alt_press(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case _:  # pragma: no cover\n+                # Don't handle other button presses\n+                pass\n+\n+    def mouseDoubleClickEvent(self, event: QMouseEvent) -> None:\n+        if event.button() == Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton:\n+            self.interface.on_activate(\n+                int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+            )\n+        else:  # pragma: no cover\n+            # Don't handle other button double-clicks\n+            pass\n+\n+    def mouseReleaseEvent(self, event: QMouseEvent) -> None:\n+        button = event.button()\n+        match button:\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton:\n+                self.interface.on_release(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.RightButton:\n+                self.interface.on_alt_release(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case _:  # pragma: no cover\n+                # Don't handle other button releases\n+                pass\n+\n+    def mouseMoveEvent(self, event: QMouseEvent) -> None:\n+        # These will only fire when a mouse button is down, i.e. dragging\n+        button = event.button()\n+        match button:\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton:\n+                self.interface.on_drag(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case Qt.MouseButton.RightButton:\n+                self.interface.on_alt_drag(\n+                    int(event.position().x()), int(event.position().y())\n+                )\n+            case _:  # pragma: no cover\n+                # Don't handle other mouse move events\n+                pass\n+\n+\n+class Canvas(Widget):\n+    _path: QPainterPath\n+\n+    def create(self):\n+        self.native = TogaCanvas(self.interface, self)\n+\n+    def redraw(self):\n+        self.native.update()\n+\n+    def set_bounds(self, x, y, width, height):\n+        super().set_bounds(x, y, width, height)\n+        self.interface.on_resize(width=width, height=height)\n+\n+    # Context management\n+    def push_context(self, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.save()\n+\n+    def pop_context(self, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.restore()\n+\n+    # Basic paths\n+    def begin_path(self, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        # QPainter doesn't have the notion of a \"current path\" so we need to track it.\n+        self._path = QPainterPath()\n+\n+    def close_path(self, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        self._path.closeSubpath()\n+\n+    def move_to(self, x, y, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        self._path.moveTo(x, y)\n+\n+    def line_to(self, x, y, draw_context, **kwargs):\n+        if self._path.elementCount() == 0:\n+            self._path.moveTo(x, y)\n+        else:\n+            self._path.lineTo(x, y)\n+\n+    # Basic shapes\n+\n+    def bezier_curve_to(\n+        self,\n+        cp1x,\n+        cp1y,\n+        cp2x,\n+        cp2y,\n+        x,\n+        y,\n+        draw_context,\n+        **kwargs,\n+    ):\n+        self._path.cubicTo(cp1x, cp1y, cp2x, cp2y, x, y)\n+\n+    def quadratic_curve_to(self, cpx, cpy, x, y, draw_context, **kwargs):\n+        self._path.quadTo(cpx, cpy, x, y)\n+\n+    def arc(\n+        self,\n+        x,\n+        y,\n+        radius,\n+        startangle,\n+        endangle,\n+        counterclockwise,\n+        draw_context,\n+        **kwargs,\n+    ):\n+        if self._path.elementCount() == 0:\n+            # if this is the first point of the path, don't draw a line\n+            # to the start point\n+            self._path.moveTo(\n+                x + radius * cos(startangle),\n+                y + radius * sin(startangle),\n+            )\n+\n+        # Qt measures angles counterclockwise from x-axis and in degrees\n+        self._path.arcTo(\n+            x - radius,\n+            y - radius,\n+            radius * 2,\n+            radius * 2,\n+            -degrees(startangle),\n+            -degrees(sweepangle(startangle, endangle, counterclockwise)),\n+        )\n+\n+    def ellipse(\n+        self,\n+        x,\n+        y,\n+        radiusx,\n+        radiusy,\n+        rotation,\n+        startangle,\n+        endangle,\n+        counterclockwise,\n+        draw_context: QPainter,\n+        **kwargs,\n+    ):\n+        # Draw the ellipse unrotated and at origin\n+        transform = QTransform()\n+        transform.translate(x, y)\n+        transform.rotate(degrees(rotation))\n+        transform.scale(radiusx, radiusy)\n+        transform.rotate(degrees(startangle))\n+\n+        # Note: we can *almost* do this using arcTo, but arcTo doesn't support rotation\n+        # (it must be axis-aligned), and attempts at manually rotating the points after\n+        # creation are awkward: easier just to use geometry routines.\n+        points = [\n+            transform.map(QPointF(x, y))\n+            for (x, y) in arc_to_bezier(\n+                sweepangle(startangle, endangle, counterclockwise)\n+            )\n+        ]\n+\n+        # draw a line to the start point unless this is the first point of the path\n+        start = points.pop(0)\n+        if self._path.elementCount() == 0:\n+            self._path.moveTo(start)\n+        else:\n+            self._path.lineTo(start)\n+\n+        for i in range(0, len(points), 3):\n+            cp1, cp2, end = points[i : i + 3]\n+            self._path.cubicTo(cp1, cp2, end)\n+\n+    def rect(self, x, y, width, height, draw_context, **kwargs):\n+        self._path.addRect(x, y, width, height)\n+\n+    # Drawing Paths\n+\n+    def _get_brush(self, fill_color, **kwargs):\n+        return native_color(fill_color)\n+\n+    def _get_pen(self, stroke_color, line_width, line_dash=None, **kwargs):\n+        pen = QPen()\n+        pen.setBrush(self._get_brush(stroke_color))\n+        pen.setCapStyle(Qt.PenCapStyle.FlatCap)\n+        pen.setWidth(line_width)\n+        if line_dash is not None:\n+            pen.setDashPattern([x / line_width for x in line_dash])\n+        return pen\n+\n+    def fill(self, color, fill_rule, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        if fill_rule == FillRule.EVENODD:\n+            self._path.setFillRule(Qt.FillRule.OddEvenFill)\n+        else:\n+            self._path.setFillRule(Qt.FillRule.WindingFill)\n+        draw_context.fillPath(self._path, self._get_brush(color))\n+\n+    def stroke(self, color, line_width, line_dash, draw_context, **kwargs):\n+        pen = self._get_pen(color, line_width, line_dash)\n+        draw_context.strokePath(self._path, pen)\n+\n+    # Transformations\n+    def rotate(self, radians, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.rotate(degrees(radians))\n+\n+    def scale(self, sx, sy, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.scale(sx, sy)\n+\n+    def translate(self, tx, ty, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.translate(tx, ty)\n+\n+    def reset_transform(self, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs):\n+        draw_context.resetTransform()\n+\n+    # Text\n+    def _text_offsets(self, text, font, line_height):\n+        metrics = QFontMetrics(font.native)\n+        if line_height is None:\n+            line_height = metrics.lineSpacing()\n+        else:\n+            line_height = line_height * font.native.pointSize()\n+\n+        sizes = [metrics.boundingRect(line) for line in text.splitlines()]\n+        if not sizes:\n+            return (0, 0, 0, 0, line_height)\n+        left_offset = ceil(min(size.x() for size in sizes))\n+        right_offset = ceil(max((size.width() + size.x()) for size in sizes))\n+        top_offset = sizes[0].y()\n+        return (\n+            left_offset,\n+            top_offset,\n+            right_offset,\n+            line_height * len(sizes) + top_offset,\n+            line_height,\n+        )\n+\n+    def measure_text(self, text, font, line_height):\n+        left, top, right, bottom, _ = self._text_offsets(text, font, line_height)\n+        return (right - left, bottom - top)\n+\n+    def write_text(\n+        self, text, x, y, font, baseline, line_height, draw_context: QPainter, **kwargs\n+    ):\n+        left_offset, top_offset, _, bottom_offset, scaled_line_height = (\n+            self._text_offsets(text, font, line_height)\n+        )\n+\n+        lines = text.splitlines()\n+        total_height = bottom_offset - top_offset\n+\n+        draw_context.save()\n+        # translate to target base point\n+        draw_context.translate(x, y)\n+\n+        # adjust for alignment\n+        if baseline == Baseline.TOP:\n+            draw_context.translate(-left_offset, -top_offset)\n+        elif baseline == Baseline.MIDDLE:\n+            draw_context.translate(-left_offset, -top_offset - (total_height / 2))\n+        elif baseline == Baseline.BOTTOM:\n+            draw_context.translate(-left_offset, -bottom_offset)\n+        else:\n+            # Default to Baseline.ALPHABETIC\n+            draw_context.translate(-left_offset, 0)\n+\n+        draw_context.setFont(font.native)\n+        path = QPainterPath()\n+        for line_num, line in enumerate(lines):\n+            y = scaled_line_height * line_num\n+            path.addText(0, y, font.native, line)\n+\n+        if \"fill_color\" in kwargs:\n+            draw_context.fillPath(path, self._get_brush(**kwargs))\n+        if \"stroke_color\" in kwargs:\n+            draw_context.strokePath(path, self._get_pen(**kwargs))\n+\n+        # reset state to how things were before translating\n+        draw_context.restore()\n+\n+    def get_image_data(self):\n+        pixmap = self.native.grab()\n+        buffer = QBuffer()\n+        buffer.open(QIODevice.WriteOnly)\n+        pixmap.save(buffer, \"PNG\")\n+        img_bytes = bytes(buffer.data())\n+        buffer.close()\n+        return img_bytes\n+\n+    # Rehint\n+    def rehint(self):\n+        size = self.native.sizeHint()\n+        self.interface.intrinsic.width = at_least(\n+            max(size.width(), self.interface._MIN_WIDTH)\n+        )\n+        self.interface.intrinsic.height = at_least(\n+            max(size.height(), self.interface._MIN_HEIGHT)\n+        )\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/qt/tests_backend/fonts.py b/qt/tests_backend/fonts.py\nindex 50035f0cf2..cb9ad73e21 100644\n--- a/qt/tests_backend/fonts.py\n+++ b/qt/tests_backend/fonts.py\n@@ -42,7 +42,7 @@ def assert_font_family(self, expected):\n \n     def assert_font_size(self, expected):\n         if expected != SYSTEM_DEFAULT_FONT_SIZE:\n-            assert self.font.pointSize() == expected\n+            assert self.font.pointSizeF() == expected\n \n     def assert_font_options(self, weight=NORMAL, style=NORMAL, variant=NORMAL):\n         assert (\ndiff --git a/qt/tests_backend/widgets/canvas.py b/qt/tests_backend/widgets/canvas.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..80d51e8af7\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/qt/tests_backend/widgets/canvas.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,94 @@\n+from io import BytesIO\n+\n+from PIL import Image\n+from PySide6.QtCore import QCoreApplication, QEvent, QPoint, Qt\n+from PySide6.QtGui import QMouseEvent\n+from toga_qt.widgets.canvas import TogaCanvas\n+\n+from .base import SimpleProbe\n+\n+\n+class CanvasProbe(SimpleProbe):\n+    native_class = TogaCanvas\n+\n+    def reference_variant(self, reference):\n+        if reference in {\"multiline_text\", \"write_text\", \"write_text_and_path\"}:\n+            return f\"{reference}-qt\"\n+        else:\n+            return reference\n+\n+    def get_image(self):\n+        return Image.open(BytesIO(self.impl.get_image_data()))\n+\n+    def _emit_event(\n+        self,\n+        event_type: QEvent.Type,\n+        x,\n+        y,\n+        button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton,\n+    ):\n+        pos = QPoint(x, y)\n+        global_pos = self.native.mapToGlobal(pos)\n+        event = QMouseEvent(\n+            event_type, pos, global_pos, button, button, Qt.KeyboardModifier.NoModifier\n+        )\n+        app = QCoreApplication.instance()\n+        app.postEvent(self.native, event)\n+\n+    async def mouse_press(self, x, y):\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonPress, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+\n+    async def mouse_activate(self, x, y):\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonPress, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonDblClick, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+\n+    async def mouse_drag(self, x1, y1, x2, y2):\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonPress, x1, y1, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseMove,\n+            (x1 + x2) // 2,\n+            (y1 + y2) // 2,\n+            button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton,\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x2, y2, button=Qt.MouseButton.LeftButton\n+        )\n+\n+    async def alt_mouse_press(self, x, y):\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonPress, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.RightButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x, y, button=Qt.MouseButton.RightButton\n+        )\n+\n+    async def alt_mouse_drag(self, x1, y1, x2, y2):\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonPress, x1, y1, button=Qt.MouseButton.RightButton\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseMove,\n+            (x1 + x2) // 2,\n+            (y1 + y2) // 2,\n+            button=Qt.MouseButton.RightButton,\n+        )\n+        self._emit_event(\n+            QEvent.Type.MouseButtonRelease, x2, y2, button=Qt.MouseButton.RightButton\n+        )\ndiff --git a/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/multiline_text-qt.png b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/multiline_text-qt.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..74b848b5ae\nBinary files /dev/null and b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/multiline_text-qt.png differ\ndiff --git a/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text-qt.png b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text-qt.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..3e5ef36791\nBinary files /dev/null and b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text-qt.png differ\ndiff --git a/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text_and_path-qt.png b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text_and_path-qt.png\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..e9acdf5e36\nBinary files /dev/null and b/testbed/src/testbed/resources/canvas/write_text_and_path-qt.png differ\n", "problem_statement": "[Qt] Tests Don't Upload App Data\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen running tests of the testbed app in CI, the test runner is supposed to bundle and upload the app's data directory. This is particularly useful as Canvas rendering failures are saved there.\n\nThis fails, because the Qt testbed app is called `testbed-qt`, but the CI script looks for `testbed`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRun a test with failures in the Qt backend on GitHub. Look at logs of the CI run on GitHub.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe app's data directory should be uploaded as an artefact.\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: Linux\n- Python version: Any\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: current GitHub main\n\n\n### Logs\n\n```\ncp: cannot stat '/home/runner/.local/share/testbed': No such file or directory\nError: Process completed with exit code 1.\n```\n\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Good job on catching this bug and how to fix it!!!\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/e044092f1cec367bb507434514bf1bcbb0e1ce9c", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/807f78f79900497ee131fc0030ecd6ccd21abde8", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/e0f4c3a1824682ca13fe272584b0a48cac63c4cd", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/58ec895cef858b950ebcdd1819b224b004ab5f74", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/9d1a96846ff890f48f8808532bb8a6c8d36e8d9b", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f12474ae815b2abd8c19d1ea9a8fd2aa035d594c", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/0ca019c68a5f91174f4e30da5e8191ed73b7ceeb", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/85bf6c0bcf995f2d31cf640a3f34273971c5fe59", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/4d3ab8e8b09615b1e8973668c07bc0db1fb62e44", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/55f699163122241d613aeb4e19cbca2f2d8afb1e", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/83053d161a9fe4e82d2b571be774d4765e9c349b", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/38c85fad05471f299aa77c1fcf134bb3572a0692", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/1c8a516ed00e1213c9bf13f734823491f78dfd36", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/61ebcf3cad2f4a5338915ca16621a62a01e5f099", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/e632b1262f060fa12fdfe5195d79a9d99522fe5f", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/4be5453c8272cb2cb16b748220bba0522196372d", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/07283178d04b8ba0801df7b184c13af777693040", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/72a6141cfc5cc72d8d9d5653c644b3f6e368bf8f", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/33cc8eaa0290bff9826a4e7ed3fee1fae13d23a6", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/56bac1f776ab57c0504a81481429bfdd519bc47b", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f9271617cdbe9c33b819d7a5c8aa73f4e1e611b3"], "created_at": "2025-12-18T13:41:13Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 149, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-149", "issue_numbers": [4017], "base_commit": "63bf69bb14f2031d156ac6de40936019649610fa", "patch": "diff --git a/src/gtk/toga_gtk/__init__.py b/src/gtk/toga_gtk/__init__.py\nindex af4f0c9395..285fbf5c88 100644\n--- a/src/gtk/toga_gtk/__init__.py\n+++ b/src/gtk/toga_gtk/__init__.py\n@@ -11,7 +11,7 @@\n from .widgets.label import *\n # from .widgets.multilinetextinput import *\n from .widgets.optioncontainer import *\n-# from .widgets.passwordinput import *\n+from .widgets.passwordinput import *\n # from .widgets.progressbar import *\n from .widgets.scrollcontainer import *\n from .widgets.splitcontainer import *\n@@ -34,7 +34,7 @@\n     'Label',\n     # 'MultilineTextInput',\n     'OptionContainer',\n-    # 'PasswordInput',\n+    'PasswordInput',\n     # 'ProgressBar',\n     'Selection',\n     'NumberInput',\ndiff --git a/src/gtk/toga_gtk/widgets/passwordinput.py b/src/gtk/toga_gtk/widgets/passwordinput.py\nindex 431136f634..212b82ce3d 100644\n--- a/src/gtk/toga_gtk/widgets/passwordinput.py\n+++ b/src/gtk/toga_gtk/widgets/passwordinput.py\n@@ -7,6 +7,6 @@ class PasswordInput(TextInput):\n     def __init__(self):\n         super(PasswordInput, self).__init__()\n \n-    def startup(self):\n-        super(PasswordInput, self).startup()\n+    def create(self):\n+        super(PasswordInput, self).create()\n         self._impl.set_visibility(False)\ndiff --git a/src/winforms/toga_winforms/__init__.py b/src/winforms/toga_winforms/__init__.py\nindex a94f37ce60..30a80e9ed4 100644\n--- a/src/winforms/toga_winforms/__init__.py\n+++ b/src/winforms/toga_winforms/__init__.py\n@@ -15,7 +15,7 @@\n from .widgets.label import *\n # from .widgets.multilinetextinput import *\n # from .widgets.optioncontainer import *\n-# from .widgets.passwordinput import *\n+from .widgets.passwordinput import *\n # from .widgets.progressbar import *\n # from .widgets.scrollcontainer import *\n # from .widgets.splitcontainer import *\n@@ -41,13 +41,13 @@\n     # 'MultilineTextInput',\n     # 'NumberInput',\n     # 'OptionContainer',\n-    # 'PasswordInput',\n     # 'ProgressBar',\n     # 'ScrollContainer',\n     # 'Selection',\n     # 'SplitContainer',\n     # 'Table',\n     'TextInput',\n+    'PasswordInput',\n     # 'Tree',\n     'WebView',\n ]\ndiff --git a/src/winforms/toga_winforms/widgets/passwordinput.py b/src/winforms/toga_winforms/widgets/passwordinput.py\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..1b57a2d472\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/src/winforms/toga_winforms/widgets/passwordinput.py\n@@ -0,0 +1,12 @@\n+from __future__ import print_function, absolute_import, division\n+\n+from .textinput import TextInput\n+\n+\n+class PasswordInput(TextInput):\n+    def __init__(self):\n+        super(PasswordInput, self).__init__()\n+\n+    def create(self):\n+        super(PasswordInput, self).create()\n+        self._impl.UseSystemPasswordChar = True\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Differentiate sections headers that are/aren't links\n### What is the problem or limitation you are having?\n\nWith the [navigation.indexes](https://squidfunk.github.io/mkdocs-material/setup/setting-up-navigation/#section-index-pages) setting, Material for MkDocs makes the top-level listing of a section a link to its own index (if present), rather than linking to it separately at the top of the section's contents. (More generally, it allows assigning the section header as a link, potentially to elsewhere.) I like that, but what I don't like is that there's no visual indication whether a section header is a link or not.\n\n<img width=\"270\" height=\"346\" alt=\"Screenshot of nav\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/753d05a6-11f9-42e2-bd2b-f7937b3a67c0\" />\n\nFor Topic Guides, Reference, and API Reference, clicking on the arrow will expand or collapse the section, while clicking on the text (or anywhere between the two) is a link that will take you to the respective documentation page.\n\nThere is no Containers page. Clicking anywhere on Containers (even on the text) just expands or collapses the section.\n\nThis difference in behavior makes perfect sense based on how the documentation is structured, but there's no way to tell the difference by looking at it.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like\n\nI'd really prefer if the non-link section titles were the color of normal text, not links. (The arrow could still be link-colored).\n\nI might even prefer that only the arrow is clickable, to be more consistent with the others, but that's less of an issue.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered\n\nWe could always turn off the indexes option, so the index pages are explicitly listed. But I prefer the listing as it is \u2014 especially if I'm putting Image format plugins and Validators as sub-items of Image and TextInput, respectively, as part of #3941. I think this makes more sense:\n\n<img width=\"239\" height=\"70\" alt=\"index in section header\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f518e389-915b-455c-b52a-6949346fdc2b\" />\n\nthan this:\n\n<img width=\"246\" height=\"103\" alt=\"separate index\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/868bb452-95dc-4d8a-933a-3b5010c6796b\" />\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thanks for the report. I have a couple of ideas. I'll look into it soon.\nFound the solution. Noting it here for my own info. I'll submit the PR next week. \n\nLine 307 becomes `a.md-nav__link`. \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/88a845aedd0b95e7854114a65f79ab4e092e4a04"], "created_at": "2017-04-25T08:32:11Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4031, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4031", "issue_numbers": [4029], "base_commit": "97e1b027bf5e1891f0de525c430a133b661efcf1", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/4029.bugfix.md b/changes/4029.bugfix.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..4c4441ac50\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/4029.bugfix.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+Setting an item in a ListSource now gives a \"change\" instead of an \"insert\" notification.\ndiff --git a/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py b/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\nindex 7adb21b4a5..2e918e4791 100644\n--- a/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\n+++ b/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\n@@ -176,7 +176,7 @@ def __setitem__(self, index: int, value: object) -> None:\n         \"\"\"\n         row = self._create_row(value)\n         self._data[index] = row\n-        self.notify(\"insert\", index=index, item=row)\n+        self.notify(\"change\", item=row)\n \n     def clear(self) -> None:\n         \"\"\"Clear all data from the data source.\"\"\"\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/core/tests/sources/test_list_source.py b/core/tests/sources/test_list_source.py\nindex e648e9d4f6..2941ba1979 100644\n--- a/core/tests/sources/test_list_source.py\n+++ b/core/tests/sources/test_list_source.py\n@@ -92,7 +92,7 @@ def test_tuples():\n     assert source[1].val1 == \"new element\"\n     assert source[1].val2 == 999\n \n-    listener.insert.assert_called_once_with(index=1, item=source[1])\n+    listener.change.assert_called_once_with(item=source[1])\n \n \n def test_list():\n@@ -125,7 +125,7 @@ def test_list():\n     assert source[1].val1 == \"new element\"\n     assert source[1].val2 == 999\n \n-    listener.insert.assert_called_once_with(index=1, item=source[1])\n+    listener.change.assert_called_once_with(item=source[1])\n \n \n def test_dict():\n@@ -158,7 +158,7 @@ def test_dict():\n     assert source[1].val1 == \"new element\"\n     assert source[1].val2 == 999\n \n-    listener.insert.assert_called_once_with(index=1, item=source[1])\n+    listener.change.assert_called_once_with(item=source[1])\n \n \n def test_flat_list():\n", "problem_statement": "`ListSource.__setitem__` notifies \"insert\" rather than \"change\"\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen an item is replaced in a `ListSource` it notifies its listeners with an `\"insert\"` message: https://github.com/beeware/toga/blob/97e1b027bf5e1891f0de525c430a133b661efcf1/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py#L170-L179\n\nFor comparison, in the `TreeSource` in equivalent code, it notifies with a `\"change\"` message: https://github.com/beeware/toga/blob/97e1b027bf5e1891f0de525c430a133b661efcf1/core/src/toga/sources/tree_source.py#L282-L295\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nCreate a `ListSource` and connect a listener to it, set an item using indexing notation, observe that the insert handler fires.\n``` python\nclass Item:\n    def __init__(self, value):\n        self.value = value\n\nclass Listener:\n    def changed(self, item):\n        print(\"change {item}\")\n    def insert(self, index, item):\n        print(\"insert {index} {item}\")\n\ndata = ListSource([\"value\"], [Item(0)])\nlistener = Listener()\ndata.add_listener(listener)\ndata[0] = Item(1)\n```\nThis will print \"insert 0 <Item ...>\" instead of \"change <Item ...>\".\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`ListSource.__setitem__` should notify its listeners with a `\"change\"` message.\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: Any\n- Python version: Any\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: Current GitHub main\n\n\n### Logs\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis is important for the Qt `DetailedList` and `Table` widget implementations. Qt distinguishes between \"insertion\" which adds rows at a location, and \"change\" which simply invalidates cell values. Until this is fixed, Qt will need to invalidate all data on an insert, rather than the more efficient insert, because it can't confidently tell Qt how many rows are being inserted.\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/4fb0d034fc9cf07ea1141c275e920b8632d9088b", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/7009b397ececcfc6593c4d04c9ed86a26cd16f3a"], "created_at": "2025-12-29T14:31:46Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4102, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4102", "issue_numbers": [4030], "base_commit": "4225b5c0cd84793f7a4ee704c985644b8740769a", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/4030.doc.md b/changes/4030.doc.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..aa78e8bf23\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/4030.doc.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+Data source topic guide now includes a discussion of how and when to connect and disconnect Listeners from Sources.\ndiff --git a/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md b/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\nindex e5e0084332..85fec3348e 100644\n--- a/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\n+++ b/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\n@@ -31,7 +31,32 @@ If any attribute of a [`ValueSource`][toga.sources.ValueSource], [`Row`][toga.so\n \n When you create a widget like Selection or Table, and provide a data source for that widget, the widget is automatically added as a listener on that source.\n \n-Although widgets are the obvious listeners for a data source, *any* object can register as a listener. For example, a second data source might register as a listener to an initial source to implement a filtered source. When an item is added to the first data source, the second data source will be notified, and can choose whether to include the new item in its own data representation.  Listeners only have to implement the methods that they need for their functionality: missing methods will be ignored.\n+Although widgets are the obvious listeners for a data source, *any* object can register as a listener. For example, a second data source might register as a listener to an initial source to implement a filtered source. When an item is added to the first data source, the second data source will be notified, and can choose whether to include the new item in its own data representation. Listeners only have to implement the methods that they need for their functionality. Missing methods will be ignored.\n+\n+You can add a listener by calling the [`add_listener`][toga.sources.base.Source.add_listener] method with your listener object. The standard data sources based off of the [`Source`][toga.sources.base.Source] class hold references to all their listeners and will continue to notify the listener as long as the data source remains in memory. When a listener is finished listening to a data source, you should call [`remove_listener`][toga.sources.base.Source.remove_listener] to remove the listener from the source.\n+\n+This is particularly important if you might change the source that the listener is listening to. When you change data source you should make sure that you remove from the old one and connect to the new one:\n+\n+``` python\n+class DataSourceListener:\n+    ...\n+    @property\n+    def data(self):\n+        return self._data\n+\n+    @data.setter\n+    def data(self, data):\n+        # disconnect as a listener on the old data source\n+        self._data.remove_listener(self)\n+        # store a reference to the new data source\n+        self._data = data\n+        # register as a listener on the new data source\n+        self._data.add_listener(self)\n+```\n+\n+If you don't disconnect, then your listener will get notifications from *both* data sources.\n+\n+Often the lifetimes of data sources are closely tied to the listeners and widgets which use them, but sometimes \u2014 particularly for custom data sources \u2014 the data source may live for a long time. In these cases you should make sure that you disconnect widgets and listeners from the data source when you no longer need them. To disconnect a widget from a source, set its [`data`][toga.widgets.table.Table.data] property to `None` (or its [`items`][toga.widgets.selection.Selection.items] to `None` for a [`Selection`][toga.widgets.selection.Selection] widget). For other listeners, call [`remove_listener`][toga.sources.base.Source.remove_listener] directly. This will improve performance, and prevent delays in garbage collection of objects that your application is no longer using.\n \n ## Custom data sources\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "`DetailedList`, `Table`, `Tree` and `Selection` widgets don't remove data listeners\n### Describe the bug\n\nIn all the `Widget` subclasses which use data sources, the `data` setter (or equivalent) *adds* the implementation as a listener to the data source but do not remove it as a listener on the old source. This means that changes to the old data source will still notify the listener, giving it spurious changes which may cause it to get into an invalid state.\n\nSee for example in `DetailedList`: https://github.com/beeware/toga/blob/97e1b027bf5e1891f0de525c430a133b661efcf1/core/src/toga/widgets/detailedlist.py#L142-L152\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nA sketch of reproduction of the error would look something like this:\n``` python\nold_data = ListSource(accessors, raw_data)\nwidget = DetailedList(data=old_data, ...)\n# do widget creation etc.\n...\nnew_data = ListSource(accessors, raw_data)\nwidget.data = new_data\nold_data.append(more_raw_data)\n# widget._impl gets its `insert` method called incorrectly.\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThere should be a call to `self._data.remove_listener(self._impl)` early in the `data` setter.\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: All\n- Python version: All\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: current GitHub main branch\n\n\n### Logs\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\nThere may be other places where `remove_listener` should be called.\n\nFor example when a widget is removed from the UI, it should almost certainly call `remove_listener` at some point but I can't see where that would be hooked in. Without this it would seem like a long-lived data source with short-lived widgets viewing it it could effectively leak memory as the data source keeps references to them as long as it is alive. A potential fix for this problem is to make the Source keep *weakrefs* to the listener, which adds complexity, but perhaps less than if there is no explicit clean-up method that allows widgets to release resources.\n", "hints_text": "Good catch - and thanks for the initial \"easy fix\" portion in #4032. \n\nAgreed that there's a memory leak risk with widget removal. Weakrefs would be one way to handle this, and would be consistent with how we historically handled the widget registry.\n\nHowever, we moved away from weakrefs in the widget registry because it became very difficult to resolve garbage collection cycles, which can have some interesting consequences because widget GC is a \"GUI operation\" in some toolkits. \n\nThe good news is that we might be able to use the same approach that we used with the widget registry - tie listeners to widget lifecycle. If we say that listeners are only installed when a widget is added to a layout, and are removed when the widget is removed, the problem should be resolved. Widgets are added/removed to the widget registry as part of the `window` setter on the base widget; if we add an extension so that listeners are added/removed as part of assigning `window`, I think that will resolve the rest of the issue you describe here.\n\nThis would be a very subtle change in behaviour - we might need to check to see if there's a need to trigger \"data source change\" events as part of the assignment process - but I can't think of a use case where an unused widget needs to be notified of a data change.\n> The good news is that we might be able to use the same approach that we used with the widget registry - tie listeners to widget lifecycle. If we say that listeners are only installed when a widget is added to a layout, and are removed when the widget is removed, the problem should be resolved. Widgets are added/removed to the widget registry as part of the `window` setter on the base widget; if we add an extension so that listeners are added/removed as part of assigning `window`, I think that will resolve the rest of the issue you describe here.\n\nThis was what I was missing in understanding the lifecycle.\n\nSo if I understand correctly, the life of a widget looks something like:\n\n- `widget.__init__` -> calls `widget.create` -> creates backend implementation object\n- potentially sometime later is added to a window -> `widget.window` is set to its window -> `widget` is in registry\n- later still it is removed from the window -> `widget.window` is set to None -> `widget._impl` still exists but with no UI parent\n\nIs it possible to re-add an existing widget back into the layout after it's been removed? Or once it's out, it's done?\n\nAnyway, it should be easy enough to add a hook that connects the implementation as a listener to the data just after the window is set (and possibly calls `change_source` as well to force a complete update) and disconnects the implementation just before the window is removed.\n> Is it possible to re-add an existing widget back into the layout after it's been removed? Or once it's out, it's done?\n\nIt's no problem to re-add a widget (or full widget tree) back in after removal. Widgets only appear in the widget registry if they're in a layout - but they can be added or removed from a layout at will. \n\nThere are a couple of workflows that rely on this - for example, Android and iOS apps don't currently have support for secondary windows; one workaround is to create the layout for a secondary window, replace the *main* window content (storing a reference to that content); and when the secondary window is \"closed\", restore the original main window content. The window example app does this as a proof of concept.\n\n> Anyway, it should be easy enough to add a hook that connects the implementation as a listener to the data just after the window is set (and possibly calls `change_source` as well to force a complete update) and disconnects the implementation just before the window is removed.\n\n+1. Sounds like that will resolve both the \"stale listener\" problem, and reduce the number of updates that are required when content in a source changes.\nI have a potential fix following the above in #4060, but because we aren't tracking individual changes when things are not in layout we have to rebuild the data when adding back. This has side-effects, most notably that the selection gets reset. I think that's fine for tables, but for the Selection widget the selection is the whole point. We can stash the value in various ways and try to restore it, but because we don't know what's happened to the list while notifications are off it may or may not make sense to restore it. This is particularly important to get right when the widget is *first* shown. So #4060 doesn't include a fix for the Selection widget.\n\nThe weakref approach for the Sources may make more sense: we're not super-concerned when things get garbage-collected, just that they do eventually, and if that means a few extra notifications to a dead widget that hasn't been GC'd yet because its in a cycle, then that's probably OK as long as it'll *eventually* get removed.\nI've gone and implemented the weak ref-base solution in #4061 and I think it's the better approach.\nI'm not sure I follow the downside you're describing. \n\nMy immediate reaction is that weakrefs are a lot more fragile than an explicit lifecycle, specifically because of the caveats that are needed around retaining references. \n\nI think I follow what you're describing regarding rebuilding - the edge case is where a data source is added to a widget, then the data changes, and then the widget is added to the page; there's a need to rebuild the widget representation to ensure that anything that was added between adding the data and adding the widget to the page is reflected in the GUI. \n\nI can see how that would cause problems; but I can't help but think there's a better solution with better lifecycle tracking - either deferring the creation of widget representation *at all* until the widget is added to layout; or optimising for the \"normal\" case - add a listener at time of *creation*, and remove on removal; but only add a listener on the second+ add to layout.\n> I'm not sure I follow the downside you're describing.\n> \n> My immediate reaction is that weakrefs are a lot more fragile than an explicit lifecycle, specifically because of the caveats that are needed around retaining references.\n\nSo the realistic problem that the weakref solution suffers from is if someone does something like the following:\n``` python\ndef connect(source, target):\n    listener = MyListener(target)\n    source.add_listener(listener)\n```\nWhat they are trying to do is to have the listener push changes to the target without the target having to be a listener. However the listener is immediately gc'd and so nothing gets pushed. But the flip-side is that this is currently a flawed design in the sense that because it never disconnects the listener, it will keep both listener and target alive (and making changes) as long as the source is alive, even if the system doesn't care about the target any more.\n\nSo it's using weakrefs is replacing a subtle bug with a more immediate one.\n\nI'm less concerned about objects not being garbage collected immediately due to gc being different on different platforms. Having a few extra notifications sent to a widget which is still alive because of a cycle is fine as long as that cycle is *eventually* collected.\n\n> I think I follow what you're describing regarding rebuilding - the edge case is where a data source is added to a widget, then the data changes, and then the widget is added to the page; there's a need to rebuild the widget representation to ensure that anything that was added between adding the data and adding the widget to the page is reflected in the GUI.\n\nThat's the first half of the problem - but re-building isn't that hard, worst case you clear and re-insert all the rows.\n\nThe real problem is with the implicit side-effects of changing the source. In particular, when you make small changes you can track the selection: removing or adding rows might change the index of the selection without removing it completely, for example. But when you stop listening the data source then you lose that tracking, and when you do a re-build you're going to lose that selection.\n\nAnd for something like a table, that's usually going to be OK: widgets were removed from the layout, changes were made to data, when you come back the selection is gone.\n\nBut for a Selection widget, the selection *is* the value and losing that value when we don't have to is problematic: at a minimum when the widget is first shown we have to match any value that was passed into the constructor.\n\nAnd even for other widgets, sometimes the selection on a table or detailedlist is also the value: you're using a table to present more information while a user selects one of the rows as the value they want.\n\nIt sounds like from the use-case you described that it would be a problem for a mobile app if a secondary window replaced the main window temporarily and when it was restored all the selections on the main window were reset: that wouldn't happen with a modal dialog in a desktop app, for example.\n\n> I can see how that would cause problems; but I can't help but think there's a better solution with better lifecycle tracking - either deferring the creation of widget representation _at all_ until the widget is added to layout; or optimising for the \"normal\" case - add a listener at time of _creation_, and remove on removal; but only add a listener on the second+ add to layout.\n\nGiven the above I sort of feel that removal of the widget from the layout isn't the right signal for disconnection of listeners. We really want some sort of \"I'm really done\" signal from the widget: being garbage collected is one such signal (and has the advantage of also working for non-widget listeners), but there could be others, such as an explicit \"destroy\" or \"disconnect\" method on widgets together with documentation on how/when to use them if they can't be invoked automatically.\n\nOr alternatively, some distinction between when a widget is removed because it is being \"hidden\" vs. when it is removed because it is being \"destroyed\". So if a widget is removed from layout with a \"hidden\" flag set, it continues to listen, but if it doesn't then it's OK to turn off listeners and re-build completely if it is re-added later.\n\nSo in summary I don't think there is a good user-transparent fix: #4060 tries that and I don't think it will work well. #4061 is small and self-contained, but does introduce weakrefs. Something like #4060 would work with the addition of some signal of intent from the user about *why* the widget is being removed, and that requires teaching the users to either explicitly show/hide, or explicitly create/destroy.\n> The real problem is with the implicit side-effects of changing the source. In particular, when you make small changes you can track the selection: removing or adding rows might change the index of the selection without removing it completely, for example. But when you stop listening the data source then you lose that tracking, and when you do a re-build you're going to lose that selection.\n> \n> And for something like a table, that's usually going to be OK: widgets were removed from the layout, changes were made to data, when you come back the selection is gone.\n> \n> But for a Selection widget, the selection _is_ the value and losing that value when we don't have to is problematic: at a minimum when the widget is first shown we have to match any value that was passed into the constructor.\n\nOk - I think I see the problem now. It really comes down to the fact that Selection's backend API is heavily based on \"index\", but if you're not getting regular updates on an index-altering changes, your visual representation has a problem, because there's no way to tell if the interpretation of \"index 3\" has changed in the interim.\n\n> Given the above I sort of feel that removal of the widget from the layout isn't the right signal for disconnection of listeners. We really want some sort of \"I'm really done\" signal from the widget: being garbage collected is one such signal (and has the advantage of also working for non-widget listeners), but there could be others, such as an explicit \"destroy\" or \"disconnect\" method on widgets together with documentation on how/when to use them if they can't be invoked automatically.\n\nAgreed that it would be desirable to hook this into garbage collection, but AFAICT that's the root of the problem here - the listener is retaining a reference to the widget, which prevents garbage collection of the widget when it's no longer being used by anything else in the system. \n\n> So in summary I don't think there is a good user-transparent fix.\n\nThinking about this... *do* we have to do something about this? I don't deny there are potential memory leaks with some usage patterns - but... are there any usage patterns that leak that *aren't* pathological? \n\nThe core reproduction case I can think of is the situation of an app that defines an external data source, then uses that data source repeatedly in widgets:\n```\ndata = ListSource(...)\n\nfor i in range(1000):\n   widget = Selection(data=data)\n```\n\nThat code *will* leak, because `data` ends up with 1000 listeners, and won't ever garbage collect them because the source owns the listener... but is that a reasonable use case to be concerned about? Is that a usage pattern that we're likely to see in practice? And, if it is - would it be reasonable to document that limitation, rather than going to extraordinary lengths to avoid it? \n\nAs far as I can tell, the following code:\n```\ndata = ListSource(...)\n\nfor i in range(1000):\n   widget = Selection(data=data)\n   widget.data = []\n```\n\n*wouldn't* leak (at least, it won't post-#4032); while widget *does* have a listener, it's on a freshly created source that is only referenced by widget, so it *should* get garbage collected after a cycle or two. \n\nI think you've convinced me that if we're going to do something about this, weakref is about as good as we're going to get... but do we actually need to do something about this, other than document it as a known issue?\n> Thinking about this... do we have to do something about this? I don't deny there are potential memory leaks with some usage patterns - but... are there any usage patterns that leak that aren't pathological?\n\nYour first example is the one that concerns me most, particularly with a custom data source and added in, as it's a \"natural\" optimisation from the second example. And while 1000 widgets seems a lot, it may not be if they were widgets in a table column.\n\nBut there is a fix in situations where this might be a problem, and that's simply to make sure that the widget releases the data when it is done via something as simple as doing `widget.data = None` when the app knows it is done with the widget, since the fix in #4032 ensures that the references are cleaned up.\n\nSo maybe a note in the data source documentation encouraging a clean-up pattern of setting data sources to None when you're done using them?\n\nThat's probably a solution in the short-term that will allow anyone who genuinely gets into difficulty because of this issue a way to fix it. And if in the future it starts being a problem for lots of people, then we know how to fix it.\nAnother possible solution to throw into the mix: have two implementations of the `Source` protocol.\n- the standard one with strong references. This is what `ListSource`, `TreeSource` etc. use.\n- a \"WeakSource\" with weak references which custom data sources can use as a base if they want\n\nThis basically allows users to opt-in to a weakref-based system if they need it in their apps.\n> Your first example is the one that concerns me most, particularly with a custom data source and added in, as it's a \"natural\" optimisation from the second example. And while 1000 widgets seems a lot, it may not be if they were widgets in a table column.\n\nThe support of widgets in tables is very much a macOS-only thing at present; I'm not convinced we've got that implementation correct. There's a lot of optimization needed to make sure that a 1000 row table *doesn't* create 1000 widgets - the Android table is what happens when you do that, and... hilarity ensues :-)\n \n> So maybe a note in the data source documentation encouraging a clean-up pattern of setting data sources to None when you're done using them?\n\nSounds like that might be the best approach for now. As you say - if it turns out to be an actual problem in practice, we can revisit this in future; but a documentation-based solution for now should do the job.\n\n> Another possible solution to throw into the mix: have two implementations of the `Source` protocol.\n\nHrm... I see what you're suggesting here but I don't know if we want to get into that game. To my mind, ListSource and TreeSource should only exist as internal stop-gap measures; if an end user can't easily implement a Source-compliant class of their own, then we've made that protocol too complex. \n\n---\n\nOn that basis, I'm going to convert this into a documentation issue. Thanks for the discussion around this!\n\n\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Good catch - and thanks for the initial \"easy fix\" portion in #4032. \n\nAgreed that there's a memory leak risk with widget removal. Weakrefs would be one way to handle this, and would be consistent with how we historically handled the widget registry.\n\nHowever, we moved away from weakrefs in the widget registry because it became very difficult to resolve garbage collection cycles, which can have some interesting consequences because widget GC is a \"GUI operation\" in some toolkits. \n\nThe good news is that we might be able to use the same approach that we used with the widget registry - tie listeners to widget lifecycle. If we say that listeners are only installed when a widget is added to a layout, and are removed when the widget is removed, the problem should be resolved. Widgets are added/removed to the widget registry as part of the `window` setter on the base widget; if we add an extension so that listeners are added/removed as part of assigning `window`, I think that will resolve the rest of the issue you describe here.\n\nThis would be a very subtle change in behaviour - we might need to check to see if there's a need to trigger \"data source change\" events as part of the assignment process - but I can't think of a use case where an unused widget needs to be notified of a data change.\n> The good news is that we might be able to use the same approach that we used with the widget registry - tie listeners to widget lifecycle. If we say that listeners are only installed when a widget is added to a layout, and are removed when the widget is removed, the problem should be resolved. Widgets are added/removed to the widget registry as part of the `window` setter on the base widget; if we add an extension so that listeners are added/removed as part of assigning `window`, I think that will resolve the rest of the issue you describe here.\n\nThis was what I was missing in understanding the lifecycle.\n\nSo if I understand correctly, the life of a widget looks something like:\n\n- `widget.__init__` -> calls `widget.create` -> creates backend implementation object\n- potentially sometime later is added to a window -> `widget.window` is set to its window -> `widget` is in registry\n- later still it is removed from the window -> `widget.window` is set to None -> `widget._impl` still exists but with no UI parent\n\nIs it possible to re-add an existing widget back into the layout after it's been removed? Or once it's out, it's done?\n\nAnyway, it should be easy enough to add a hook that connects the implementation as a listener to the data just after the window is set (and possibly calls `change_source` as well to force a complete update) and disconnects the implementation just before the window is removed.\n> Is it possible to re-add an existing widget back into the layout after it's been removed? Or once it's out, it's done?\n\nIt's no problem to re-add a widget (or full widget tree) back in after removal. Widgets only appear in the widget registry if they're in a layout - but they can be added or removed from a layout at will. \n\nThere are a couple of workflows that rely on this - for example, Android and iOS apps don't currently have support for secondary windows; one workaround is to create the layout for a secondary window, replace the *main* window content (storing a reference to that content); and when the secondary window is \"closed\", restore the original main window content. The window example app does this as a proof of concept.\n\n> Anyway, it should be easy enough to add a hook that connects the implementation as a listener to the data just after the window is set (and possibly calls `change_source` as well to force a complete update) and disconnects the implementation just before the window is removed.\n\n+1. Sounds like that will resolve both the \"stale listener\" problem, and reduce the number of updates that are required when content in a source changes.\nI have a potential fix following the above in #4060, but because we aren't tracking individual changes when things are not in layout we have to rebuild the data when adding back. This has side-effects, most notably that the selection gets reset. I think that's fine for tables, but for the Selection widget the selection is the whole point. We can stash the value in various ways and try to restore it, but because we don't know what's happened to the list while notifications are off it may or may not make sense to restore it. This is particularly important to get right when the widget is *first* shown. So #4060 doesn't include a fix for the Selection widget.\n\nThe weakref approach for the Sources may make more sense: we're not super-concerned when things get garbage-collected, just that they do eventually, and if that means a few extra notifications to a dead widget that hasn't been GC'd yet because its in a cycle, then that's probably OK as long as it'll *eventually* get removed.\nI've gone and implemented the weak ref-base solution in #4061 and I think it's the better approach.\nI'm not sure I follow the downside you're describing. \n\nMy immediate reaction is that weakrefs are a lot more fragile than an explicit lifecycle, specifically because of the caveats that are needed around retaining references. \n\nI think I follow what you're describing regarding rebuilding - the edge case is where a data source is added to a widget, then the data changes, and then the widget is added to the page; there's a need to rebuild the widget representation to ensure that anything that was added between adding the data and adding the widget to the page is reflected in the GUI. \n\nI can see how that would cause problems; but I can't help but think there's a better solution with better lifecycle tracking - either deferring the creation of widget representation *at all* until the widget is added to layout; or optimising for the \"normal\" case - add a listener at time of *creation*, and remove on removal; but only add a listener on the second+ add to layout.\n> I'm not sure I follow the downside you're describing.\n> \n> My immediate reaction is that weakrefs are a lot more fragile than an explicit lifecycle, specifically because of the caveats that are needed around retaining references.\n\nSo the realistic problem that the weakref solution suffers from is if someone does something like the following:\n``` python\ndef connect(source, target):\n    listener = MyListener(target)\n    source.add_listener(listener)\n```\nWhat they are trying to do is to have the listener push changes to the target without the target having to be a listener. However the listener is immediately gc'd and so nothing gets pushed. But the flip-side is that this is currently a flawed design in the sense that because it never disconnects the listener, it will keep both listener and target alive (and making changes) as long as the source is alive, even if the system doesn't care about the target any more.\n\nSo it's using weakrefs is replacing a subtle bug with a more immediate one.\n\nI'm less concerned about objects not being garbage collected immediately due to gc being different on different platforms. Having a few extra notifications sent to a widget which is still alive because of a cycle is fine as long as that cycle is *eventually* collected.\n\n> I think I follow what you're describing regarding rebuilding - the edge case is where a data source is added to a widget, then the data changes, and then the widget is added to the page; there's a need to rebuild the widget representation to ensure that anything that was added between adding the data and adding the widget to the page is reflected in the GUI.\n\nThat's the first half of the problem - but re-building isn't that hard, worst case you clear and re-insert all the rows.\n\nThe real problem is with the implicit side-effects of changing the source. In particular, when you make small changes you can track the selection: removing or adding rows might change the index of the selection without removing it completely, for example. But when you stop listening the data source then you lose that tracking, and when you do a re-build you're going to lose that selection.\n\nAnd for something like a table, that's usually going to be OK: widgets were removed from the layout, changes were made to data, when you come back the selection is gone.\n\nBut for a Selection widget, the selection *is* the value and losing that value when we don't have to is problematic: at a minimum when the widget is first shown we have to match any value that was passed into the constructor.\n\nAnd even for other widgets, sometimes the selection on a table or detailedlist is also the value: you're using a table to present more information while a user selects one of the rows as the value they want.\n\nIt sounds like from the use-case you described that it would be a problem for a mobile app if a secondary window replaced the main window temporarily and when it was restored all the selections on the main window were reset: that wouldn't happen with a modal dialog in a desktop app, for example.\n\n> I can see how that would cause problems; but I can't help but think there's a better solution with better lifecycle tracking - either deferring the creation of widget representation _at all_ until the widget is added to layout; or optimising for the \"normal\" case - add a listener at time of _creation_, and remove on removal; but only add a listener on the second+ add to layout.\n\nGiven the above I sort of feel that removal of the widget from the layout isn't the right signal for disconnection of listeners. We really want some sort of \"I'm really done\" signal from the widget: being garbage collected is one such signal (and has the advantage of also working for non-widget listeners), but there could be others, such as an explicit \"destroy\" or \"disconnect\" method on widgets together with documentation on how/when to use them if they can't be invoked automatically.\n\nOr alternatively, some distinction between when a widget is removed because it is being \"hidden\" vs. when it is removed because it is being \"destroyed\". So if a widget is removed from layout with a \"hidden\" flag set, it continues to listen, but if it doesn't then it's OK to turn off listeners and re-build completely if it is re-added later.\n\nSo in summary I don't think there is a good user-transparent fix: #4060 tries that and I don't think it will work well. #4061 is small and self-contained, but does introduce weakrefs. Something like #4060 would work with the addition of some signal of intent from the user about *why* the widget is being removed, and that requires teaching the users to either explicitly show/hide, or explicitly create/destroy.\n> The real problem is with the implicit side-effects of changing the source. In particular, when you make small changes you can track the selection: removing or adding rows might change the index of the selection without removing it completely, for example. But when you stop listening the data source then you lose that tracking, and when you do a re-build you're going to lose that selection.\n> \n> And for something like a table, that's usually going to be OK: widgets were removed from the layout, changes were made to data, when you come back the selection is gone.\n> \n> But for a Selection widget, the selection _is_ the value and losing that value when we don't have to is problematic: at a minimum when the widget is first shown we have to match any value that was passed into the constructor.\n\nOk - I think I see the problem now. It really comes down to the fact that Selection's backend API is heavily based on \"index\", but if you're not getting regular updates on an index-altering changes, your visual representation has a problem, because there's no way to tell if the interpretation of \"index 3\" has changed in the interim.\n\n> Given the above I sort of feel that removal of the widget from the layout isn't the right signal for disconnection of listeners. We really want some sort of \"I'm really done\" signal from the widget: being garbage collected is one such signal (and has the advantage of also working for non-widget listeners), but there could be others, such as an explicit \"destroy\" or \"disconnect\" method on widgets together with documentation on how/when to use them if they can't be invoked automatically.\n\nAgreed that it would be desirable to hook this into garbage collection, but AFAICT that's the root of the problem here - the listener is retaining a reference to the widget, which prevents garbage collection of the widget when it's no longer being used by anything else in the system. \n\n> So in summary I don't think there is a good user-transparent fix.\n\nThinking about this... *do* we have to do something about this? I don't deny there are potential memory leaks with some usage patterns - but... are there any usage patterns that leak that *aren't* pathological? \n\nThe core reproduction case I can think of is the situation of an app that defines an external data source, then uses that data source repeatedly in widgets:\n```\ndata = ListSource(...)\n\nfor i in range(1000):\n   widget = Selection(data=data)\n```\n\nThat code *will* leak, because `data` ends up with 1000 listeners, and won't ever garbage collect them because the source owns the listener... but is that a reasonable use case to be concerned about? Is that a usage pattern that we're likely to see in practice? And, if it is - would it be reasonable to document that limitation, rather than going to extraordinary lengths to avoid it? \n\nAs far as I can tell, the following code:\n```\ndata = ListSource(...)\n\nfor i in range(1000):\n   widget = Selection(data=data)\n   widget.data = []\n```\n\n*wouldn't* leak (at least, it won't post-#4032); while widget *does* have a listener, it's on a freshly created source that is only referenced by widget, so it *should* get garbage collected after a cycle or two. \n\nI think you've convinced me that if we're going to do something about this, weakref is about as good as we're going to get... but do we actually need to do something about this, other than document it as a known issue?\n> Thinking about this... do we have to do something about this? I don't deny there are potential memory leaks with some usage patterns - but... are there any usage patterns that leak that aren't pathological?\n\nYour first example is the one that concerns me most, particularly with a custom data source and added in, as it's a \"natural\" optimisation from the second example. And while 1000 widgets seems a lot, it may not be if they were widgets in a table column.\n\nBut there is a fix in situations where this might be a problem, and that's simply to make sure that the widget releases the data when it is done via something as simple as doing `widget.data = None` when the app knows it is done with the widget, since the fix in #4032 ensures that the references are cleaned up.\n\nSo maybe a note in the data source documentation encouraging a clean-up pattern of setting data sources to None when you're done using them?\n\nThat's probably a solution in the short-term that will allow anyone who genuinely gets into difficulty because of this issue a way to fix it. And if in the future it starts being a problem for lots of people, then we know how to fix it.\nAnother possible solution to throw into the mix: have two implementations of the `Source` protocol.\n- the standard one with strong references. This is what `ListSource`, `TreeSource` etc. use.\n- a \"WeakSource\" with weak references which custom data sources can use as a base if they want\n\nThis basically allows users to opt-in to a weakref-based system if they need it in their apps.\n> Your first example is the one that concerns me most, particularly with a custom data source and added in, as it's a \"natural\" optimisation from the second example. And while 1000 widgets seems a lot, it may not be if they were widgets in a table column.\n\nThe support of widgets in tables is very much a macOS-only thing at present; I'm not convinced we've got that implementation correct. There's a lot of optimization needed to make sure that a 1000 row table *doesn't* create 1000 widgets - the Android table is what happens when you do that, and... hilarity ensues :-)\n \n> So maybe a note in the data source documentation encouraging a clean-up pattern of setting data sources to None when you're done using them?\n\nSounds like that might be the best approach for now. As you say - if it turns out to be an actual problem in practice, we can revisit this in future; but a documentation-based solution for now should do the job.\n\n> Another possible solution to throw into the mix: have two implementations of the `Source` protocol.\n\nHrm... I see what you're suggesting here but I don't know if we want to get into that game. To my mind, ListSource and TreeSource should only exist as internal stop-gap measures; if an end user can't easily implement a Source-compliant class of their own, then we've made that protocol too complex. \n\n---\n\nOn that basis, I'm going to convert this into a documentation issue. Thanks for the discussion around this!\n\n\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/bab6699309d5dcd806310f0c4f93328cb7585b9d", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/54293689a3567becc7482bf1ff481569e166c40c", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/873280cfec93ed3824418c80013e45b56d6837a6"], "created_at": "2026-01-19T15:00:44Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4063, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4063", "issue_numbers": [4035], "base_commit": "3b5cc1df0daaab9370ec62d8b563e4decd709cdf", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/4035.bugfix.md b/changes/4035.bugfix.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..a8782a7003\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/4035.bugfix.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+There are now different Listener protocols for `ValueSource`, `ListSource`, and `TreeSource`.\ndiff --git a/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/tree.py b/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/tree.py\nindex 2612fc93fb..ec995d9212 100644\n--- a/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/tree.py\n+++ b/cocoa/src/toga_cocoa/widgets/tree.py\n@@ -191,7 +191,7 @@ def create(self):\n     def change_source(self, source):\n         self.native_tree.reloadData()\n \n-    def insert(self, parent, index, item):\n+    def insert(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         index_set = NSIndexSet.indexSetWithIndex(index)\n         self.native_tree.insertItemsAtIndexes(\n             index_set,\n@@ -202,7 +202,7 @@ def insert(self, parent, index, item):\n     def change(self, item):\n         self.native_tree.reloadItem(node_impl(item))\n \n-    def remove(self, parent, index, item):\n+    def remove(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         try:\n             index = self.native_tree.childIndexForItem(item._impl)\n             index_set = NSIndexSet.indexSetWithIndex(index)\ndiff --git a/core/src/toga/sources/__init__.py b/core/src/toga/sources/__init__.py\nindex 1a6ce00742..d2d040f7b3 100644\n--- a/core/src/toga/sources/__init__.py\n+++ b/core/src/toga/sources/__init__.py\n@@ -1,18 +1,38 @@\n from .accessors import to_accessor  # noqa: F401\n-from .base import Listener, Source  # noqa: F401\n+from .base import (  # noqa: F401\n+    ListListener,\n+    Source,\n+    TreeListener,\n+    ValueListener,\n+)\n from .list_source import ListSource, ListSourceT, Row  # noqa: F401\n from .tree_source import Node, TreeSource, TreeSourceT  # noqa: F401\n from .value_source import ValueSource  # noqa: F401\n \n __all__ = [\n+    \"ListListener\",\n     \"ListSource\",\n     \"ListSourceT\",\n     \"Listener\",\n     \"Node\",\n     \"Row\",\n     \"Source\",\n+    \"TreeListener\",\n     \"TreeSource\",\n     \"TreeSourceT\",\n+    \"ValueListener\",\n     \"ValueSource\",\n     \"to_accessor\",\n ]\n+\n+\n+def __getattr__(name):\n+    if name == \"Listener\":\n+        # Alias for backwards compatibility:\n+        # Jan 2025: In 0.5.3 and earlier, ListListener was named Listener\n+        global Listener\n+        from .base import Listener\n+\n+        return Listener\n+    else:\n+        raise AttributeError(f\"module '{__name__}' has no attribute '{name}'\") from None\ndiff --git a/core/src/toga/sources/base.py b/core/src/toga/sources/base.py\nindex dc995f1ae2..078f77949c 100644\n--- a/core/src/toga/sources/base.py\n+++ b/core/src/toga/sources/base.py\n@@ -1,53 +1,89 @@\n from __future__ import annotations\n \n-from typing import Protocol\n+from typing import Generic, Protocol, TypeVar, runtime_checkable\n \n+ListenerT = TypeVar(\"ListenerT\")\n+ItemT = TypeVar(\"ItemT\", contravariant=True)\n \n-class Listener(Protocol):\n+\n+@runtime_checkable\n+class ValueListener(Protocol, Generic[ItemT]):\n     \"\"\"The protocol that must be implemented by objects that will act as a listener on a\n-    data source.\n+    value data source.\n     \"\"\"\n \n-    def change(self, item: object) -> object:\n+    def change(self, *, item: ItemT) -> None:\n         \"\"\"A change has occurred in an item.\n \n         :param item: The data object that has changed.\n         \"\"\"\n \n-    def insert(self, index: int, item: object) -> object:\n+\n+@runtime_checkable\n+class ListListener(ValueListener[ItemT], Protocol, Generic[ItemT]):\n+    \"\"\"The protocol that must be implemented by objects that will act as a listener on a\n+    list data source.\n+    \"\"\"\n+\n+    def insert(self, *, index: int, item: ItemT) -> None:\n         \"\"\"An item has been added to the data source.\n \n         :param index: The 0-index position in the data.\n         :param item: The data object that was added.\n         \"\"\"\n \n-    def remove(self, index: int, item: object) -> object:\n+    def remove(self, *, index: int, item: ItemT) -> None:\n         \"\"\"An item has been removed from the data source.\n \n         :param index: The 0-index position in the data.\n         :param item: The data object that was added.\n         \"\"\"\n \n-    def clear(self) -> object:\n+    def clear(self) -> None:\n         \"\"\"All items have been removed from the data source.\"\"\"\n \n \n-class Source:\n+@runtime_checkable\n+class TreeListener(ListListener[ItemT], Protocol, Generic[ItemT]):\n+    \"\"\"The protocol that must be implemented by objects that will act as a listener on a\n+    tree data source.\n+    \"\"\"\n+\n+    def insert(self, *, index: int, item: object, parent: ItemT | None = None) -> None:\n+        \"\"\"An item has been added to the data source.\n+\n+        :param index: The 0-index position in the data.\n+        :param item: The data object that was added.\n+        :param parent: The parent of the data object that was added, or `None`\n+            if it is a root item.\n+        \"\"\"\n+\n+    def remove(self, *, index: int, item: object, parent: ItemT | None = None) -> None:\n+        \"\"\"An item has been removed from the data source.\n+\n+        :param index: The 0-index position in the data.\n+        :param item: The data object that was added.\n+        :param parent: The parent of the data object that was removed, or `None`\n+            if it is a root item.\n+        \"\"\"\n+\n+\n+class Source(Generic[ListenerT]):\n     \"\"\"A base class for data sources, providing an implementation of data\n     notifications.\"\"\"\n \n     def __init__(self) -> None:\n-        self._listeners: list[Listener] = []\n+        self._listeners: list[ListenerT] = []\n \n     @property\n-    def listeners(self) -> list[Listener]:\n+    def listeners(self) -> list[ListenerT]:\n         \"\"\"The listeners of this data source.\n \n         :returns: A list of objects that are listening to this data source.\n         \"\"\"\n         return self._listeners\n \n-    def add_listener(self, listener: Listener) -> None:\n+    def add_listener(self, listener: ListenerT) -> None:\n         \"\"\"Add a new listener to this data source.\n \n         If the listener is already registered on this data source, the request to add is\n@@ -58,7 +94,7 @@ def add_listener(self, listener: Listener) -> None:\n         if listener not in self._listeners:\n             self._listeners.append(listener)\n \n-    def remove_listener(self, listener: Listener) -> None:\n+    def remove_listener(self, listener: ListenerT) -> None:\n         \"\"\"Remove a listener from this data source.\n \n         :param listener: The listener to remove.\n@@ -79,3 +115,22 @@ def notify(self, notification: str, **kwargs: object) -> None:\n \n             if method:\n                 method(**kwargs)\n+\n+\n+def __getattr__(name):\n+    if name == \"Listener\":\n+        import warnings\n+\n+        # Alias for backwards compatibility:\n+        # Jan 2025: In 0.5.3 and earlier, ListListener was named Listener\n+        global Listener\n+        Listener = ListListener\n+        warnings.warn(\n+            \"The Listener protocol has been deprecated; \"\n+            \"use ListListener or TreeListener instead.\",\n+            DeprecationWarning,\n+            stacklevel=2,\n+        )\n+        return Listener\n+    else:\n+        raise AttributeError(f\"module '{__name__}' has no attribute '{name}'\") from None\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/listsource.md b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/listsource.md\nindex 079156cee5..f9ece4d254 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/listsource.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/listsource.md\n@@ -56,6 +56,8 @@ For more complex applications, you can replace ListSource with a [custom data so\n \n ::: toga.sources.Row\n \n+::: toga.sources.ListSourceT\n+\n ::: toga.sources.ListSource\n \n-::: toga.sources.ListSourceT\n+::: toga.sources.ListListener\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/source.md b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/source.md\nindex e45a155377..47973347b0 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/source.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/source.md\n@@ -14,6 +14,4 @@ It can also be used by custom data source implementations.\n \n ## Reference\n \n-::: toga.sources.Listener\n-\n ::: toga.sources.Source\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/treesource.md b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/treesource.md\nindex 9b352b16db..4304541d2c 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/treesource.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/treesource.md\n@@ -82,6 +82,8 @@ For more complex applications, you can replace TreeSource with a [custom data so\n \n ::: toga.sources.Node\n \n+::: toga.sources.TreeSourceT\n+\n ::: toga.sources.TreeSource\n \n-::: toga.sources.TreeSourceT\n+::: toga.sources.TreeListener\ndiff --git a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/valuesource.md b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/valuesource.md\nindex 36e7452663..55e1dcc3b0 100644\n--- a/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/valuesource.md\n+++ b/docs/en/reference/api/data-representation/valuesource.md\n@@ -26,3 +26,5 @@ A custom ValueSource has 3 requirements:\n ## Reference\n \n ::: toga.sources.ValueSource\n+\n+::: toga.sources.ValueListener\ndiff --git a/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md b/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\nindex f85df0d3f0..e5e0084332 100644\n--- a/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\n+++ b/docs/en/topics/data-sources.md\n@@ -18,7 +18,9 @@ Although Toga provides these built-in data sources, in general, *you shouldn't u\n \n ### Listeners\n \n-Data sources communicate using a [`Listener`][toga.sources.Listener] interface. When any significant event occurs to the data source, all listeners will be notified. This includes:\n+Data sources communicate using a `Listener` interface which specifies the methods a listener object should implement to handle particular change notifications. Each type of Source has a corresponding Listener interface: [`ValueListener`][toga.sources.ValueListener], [`ListListener`][toga.sources.ListListener] and [`TreeListener`][toga.sources.TreeListener].\n+\n+When any significant event occurs to the data source, all listeners will be notified. This includes:\n \n - Adding a new item\n - Removing an existing item\n@@ -29,10 +31,10 @@ If any attribute of a [`ValueSource`][toga.sources.ValueSource], [`Row`][toga.so\n \n When you create a widget like Selection or Table, and provide a data source for that widget, the widget is automatically added as a listener on that source.\n \n-Although widgets are the obvious listeners for a data source, *any* object can register as a listener. For example, a second data source might register as a listener to an initial source to implement a filtered source. When an item is added to the first data source, the second data source will be notified, and can choose whether to include the new item in its own data representation.\n+Although widgets are the obvious listeners for a data source, *any* object can register as a listener. For example, a second data source might register as a listener to an initial source to implement a filtered source. When an item is added to the first data source, the second data source will be notified, and can choose whether to include the new item in its own data representation.  Listeners only have to implement the methods that they need for their functionality: missing methods will be ignored.\n \n ## Custom data sources\n \n A custom data source enables you to provide a data manipulation API that makes sense for your application. For example, if you were writing an application to display files on a file system, you shouldn't just build a dictionary of files, and use that to construct a [`TreeSource`][toga.sources.TreeSource]. Instead, you should write your own `FileSystemSource` that reflects the files on the file system. Your file system data source doesn't need to expose `insert()` or `remove()` methods - because the end user doesn't need an interface to \"insert\" files into your file system. However, you might have a `create_empty_file()` method that creates a new file in the file system and adds a representation to the data tree.\n \n-Custom data sources are also required to emit notifications whenever notable events occur. This allows the widgets rendering the data source to respond to changes in data. If a data source doesn't emit notifications, widgets may not reflect changes in data. Toga provides a [`Source`][toga.sources.Source] base class for custom data source implementations. This base class implements the notification API.\n+Custom data sources are also required to emit notifications whenever notable events occur. This allows the widgets rendering the data source to respond to changes in data. To be used as a data source for a particular widget type, the custom data source must emit compatible notifications. If a data source doesn't emit notifications, widgets may not reflect changes in data. Toga provides a [`Source`][toga.sources.Source] base class for custom data source implementations. This base class implements the notification API.\ndiff --git a/dummy/src/toga_dummy/widgets/tree.py b/dummy/src/toga_dummy/widgets/tree.py\nindex a5d45edfbe..5b15118c80 100644\n--- a/dummy/src/toga_dummy/widgets/tree.py\n+++ b/dummy/src/toga_dummy/widgets/tree.py\n@@ -19,13 +19,13 @@ def change_source(self, source):\n         self._action(\"change source\", source=source)\n         self.interface.on_select()\n \n-    def insert(self, parent, index, item):\n+    def insert(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         self._action(\"insert node\", parent=parent, index=index, item=item)\n \n     def change(self, item):\n         self._action(\"change node\", item=item)\n \n-    def remove(self, parent, item, index):\n+    def remove(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         self._action(\"remove node\", parent=parent, index=index, item=item)\n \n     def clear(self):\ndiff --git a/gtk/src/toga_gtk/widgets/tree.py b/gtk/src/toga_gtk/widgets/tree.py\nindex 8076a62cdb..0cee38a199 100644\n--- a/gtk/src/toga_gtk/widgets/tree.py\n+++ b/gtk/src/toga_gtk/widgets/tree.py\n@@ -82,14 +82,14 @@ def change_source(self, source):\n             self.store = Gtk.TreeStore(*types)\n \n             for i, row in enumerate(self.interface.data):\n-                self.insert(None, i, row)\n+                self.insert(parent=None, index=i, item=row)\n \n             self.native_tree.set_model(self.store)\n             self.refresh()\n         else:  # pragma: no-cover-if-gtk3\n             pass\n \n-    def insert(self, parent, index, item):\n+    def insert(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         row = TogaRow(item)\n         values = [row]\n         for column in self.interface._columns:\n@@ -109,7 +109,7 @@ def insert(self, parent, index, item):\n         item._impl = self.store.insert(iter, index, values)\n \n         for i, child in enumerate(item):\n-            self.insert(item, i, child)\n+            self.insert(parent=item, index=i, item=child)\n \n     def change(self, item):\n         row = self.store[item._impl]\n@@ -118,7 +118,7 @@ def change(self, item):\n             row[i * 2 + 2] = row[0].text(column, self.interface.missing_value)\n             row[0].warn_widget(column)\n \n-    def remove(self, item, index, parent):\n+    def remove(self, index, item, parent=None):\n         del self.store[item._impl]\n         item._impl = None\n \n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/core/tests/sources/test_source.py b/core/tests/sources/test_source.py\nindex 00434976e5..5649b2d8c3 100644\n--- a/core/tests/sources/test_source.py\n+++ b/core/tests/sources/test_source.py\n@@ -1,5 +1,7 @@\n from unittest.mock import Mock\n \n+import pytest\n+\n from toga.sources import Source\n \n \n@@ -67,3 +69,40 @@ def test_missing_listener_method():\n     source.notify(\"message1\")\n \n     full_listener.message1.assert_called_once_with()\n+\n+\n+def test_deprecate_listener():\n+    import toga.sources.base\n+\n+    # Import Listener from toga.sources.base. Raises a deprecation warning.\n+    with pytest.warns(\n+        DeprecationWarning,\n+        match=r\"The Listener protocol has been deprecated;\",\n+    ):\n+        from toga.sources.base import Listener\n+\n+    assert Listener is toga.sources.base.ListListener\n+\n+    with pytest.raises(\n+        ImportError,\n+        match=r\"cannot import name 'NonExistent' from 'toga.sources.base'\",\n+    ):\n+        from toga.sources.base import NonExistent  # noqa: F401\n+\n+    # \"unimport\" Listener\n+    del toga.sources.base.Listener\n+\n+    # Import Listener from toga.sources.base. Raises a deprecation warning.\n+    with pytest.warns(\n+        DeprecationWarning,\n+        match=r\"The Listener protocol has been deprecated;\",\n+    ):\n+        from toga.sources import Listener\n+\n+    assert Listener is toga.sources.base.ListListener\n+\n+    with pytest.raises(\n+        ImportError,\n+        match=r\"cannot import name 'NonExistent' from 'toga.sources'\",\n+    ):\n+        from toga.sources import NonExistent  # noqa: F401\ndiff --git a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_detailedlist.py b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_detailedlist.py\nindex ec2f20dcf0..ff749fe5c3 100644\n--- a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_detailedlist.py\n+++ b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_detailedlist.py\n@@ -3,7 +3,7 @@\n import pytest\n \n import toga\n-from toga.sources import ListSource\n+from toga.sources import ListListener, ListSource\n from toga.style.pack import Pack\n \n from .conftest import build_cleanup_test\n@@ -318,3 +318,8 @@ async def test_actions(\n     await probe.redraw(\"A primary action was performed on row 6\")\n     on_primary_action_handler.assert_called_once_with(widget, row=widget.data[6])\n     on_primary_action_handler.reset_mock()\n+\n+\n+def test_list_listener(widget):\n+    \"\"\"Does the widget implement the ListListener API\"\"\"\n+    assert isinstance(widget._impl, ListListener)\ndiff --git a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_selection.py b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_selection.py\nindex e23be42242..5fb309a128 100644\n--- a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_selection.py\n+++ b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_selection.py\n@@ -4,7 +4,7 @@\n \n import toga\n from toga.constants import CENTER\n-from toga.sources import ListSource\n+from toga.sources import ListListener, ListSource\n \n from .conftest import build_cleanup_test\n from .properties import (  # noqa: F401\n@@ -328,3 +328,8 @@ async def test_resize_on_content_change(widget, probe):\n     await probe.redraw(\"The long item has been renamed\")\n     if probe.shrink_on_resize:\n         assert probe.width == original_width\n+\n+\n+def test_list_listener(widget):\n+    \"\"\"Does the widget implement the ListListener API\"\"\"\n+    assert isinstance(widget._impl, ListListener)\ndiff --git a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_table.py b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_table.py\nindex adf3b2b6e3..6c51d894f0 100644\n--- a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_table.py\n+++ b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_table.py\n@@ -4,7 +4,7 @@\n import pytest\n \n import toga\n-from toga.sources import ListSource\n+from toga.sources import ListListener, ListSource\n from toga.style.pack import Pack\n \n from ..conftest import skip_on_platforms\n@@ -623,3 +623,8 @@ async def test_cell_widget(widget, probe):\n         # we just won't have widgets in the cells.\n         probe.assert_cell_content(0, 2, \"MISSING!\")\n         probe.assert_cell_content(1, 2, \"MISSING!\")\n+\n+\n+def test_list_listener(widget):\n+    \"\"\"Does the widget implement the ListListener API\"\"\"\n+    assert isinstance(widget._impl, ListListener)\ndiff --git a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_tree.py b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_tree.py\nindex e8366c0c45..637bdc456a 100644\n--- a/testbed/tests/widgets/test_tree.py\n+++ b/testbed/tests/widgets/test_tree.py\n@@ -4,7 +4,7 @@\n import pytest\n \n import toga\n-from toga.sources import TreeSource\n+from toga.sources import ListListener, TreeListener, TreeSource\n from toga.style.pack import Pack\n \n from ..conftest import skip_on_platforms\n@@ -880,3 +880,10 @@ async def test_cell_widget(widget, probe):\n         # we just won't have widgets in the cells.\n         probe.assert_cell_content((0, 0), 2, \"MISSING!\")\n         probe.assert_cell_content((0, 1), 2, \"MISSING!\")\n+\n+\n+def test_tree_listener(widget):\n+    \"\"\"Does the widget Implementation satisfy the ListListener and\n+    TreeListener APIs\"\"\"\n+    assert isinstance(widget._impl, ListListener)\n+    assert isinstance(widget._impl, TreeListener)\n", "problem_statement": "`Listener` Protocol doesn't match `TreeSource` notifications\n### Describe the bug\n\nThe `change`, `insert` and `remove` notifications generated by `TreeSource` objects pass an additional keyword argument of `parent`, which is not part of the protocol.\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nNot really a reproducible bug per-se, but you can get static type checkers to complain that something that can listen to `TreeSources` correctly is not a `Listener` and shouldn't be passed to `add_listener`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nEither\n- the `Listener` API grows a `parent=None` argument, or\n- there are multiple protocols: `ListListener`, `TreeListener`, and possibly `ValueListener`.\n\nIn the first case, there probably should be a mass-updating of backend implementations to handle the additional argument, and maybe have the `ListSource` emit `parent=None` where appropriate.\n\nThe second is a bit more awkward, but may be better if the purpose of the protocols is more to be a record of what is expected. In this case the `Source` API should be changed to reflect that there may be more than one type of listener (possibly making it generic on the listener type).\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: All\n- Python version: All\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: current GitHib main\n\n\n### Logs\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis is a largely cosmetic bug, since the `Listener` classes that should match protocol are all backend implementations of widgets, but there is I think some intent from the API that other parts of the app may want to listen for changes to data sources in user code via the source/listener API (eg. to push back changes to an underlying data structure or database).\n", "hints_text": "Agreed with the analysis here - either there's a missing argument to the protocol, or there's multiple protocols. I can imagine both working, but my gut tells me that having separate protocols is likely the better approach, as data sources with a single value will inherently have different update semantics to tree sources.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Agreed with the analysis here - either there's a missing argument to the protocol, or there's multiple protocols. I can imagine both working, but my gut tells me that having separate protocols is likely the better approach, as data sources with a single value will inherently have different update semantics to tree sources.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/b3535860ede278c385a116aaeb0f93d9d06b22f3", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/ebda91c2c9818167b2ecfd6d5ce9141bee286fd6", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/031f7a809c50319d18c59b9b3107ee5aa0fbec42", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/1056c0dcde956c57eee49b52dbdf6c77b3cfaa91", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/84c608c4aea57b657e997b3876ee0cfc7f6c0af4", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/b9180d156536d3ed310a74689c172c9776440296", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/6b1dec1f4b5d208524ac0cc382e1cfd8466e6cdb", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/66bb08603a774c70b8b2d28312977c99f0c0eaa8", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/2dabab55c210a301c947a1bcaf203d808e7b2650", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/1c56877898ef7347d80e63679266d70dacf5a310", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f04f5ef481c3b409b4e69d159f5c1d782af04ee1", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/c6e7fbd37fca5a0743f5b0e7dc98f5aa1d133d14", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f4c9820ab19125d81eff816204037c9eef4db519", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/2c16540bb9077ecb7823e56922571cf20cca9591", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/b55a9f7c09efe1166a25b3fa6199e1ba0cd0202c", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/1383cbc6aa6e1edc772dee9495743b8d15490c09", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/b8e887980922ee09034e0ff8d69bdb56f17f691d", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/3fc7137cd17095003620fa30494bdfd0a5b3bd28", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/646b872baa83bdc7d19a449eccf51151621cf5f2", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/9faf5b46ced5b8604f2ec711a75c5f48edfa4a98", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/520b181b06c88be59a65ccdc73a140eea9d12499", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/f597d67031d89b8907b4377fc0e56322fe8a2cc8", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/758319a7493629ede967d069e03811586e2557fb", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/3a8f6e0eee47890a25161dc81a0ee0a3796f084a"], "created_at": "2026-01-08T15:42:30Z"}
{"repo": "beeware/toga", "pull_number": 4038, "instance_id": "beeware__toga-4038", "issue_numbers": [4037], "base_commit": "97e1b027bf5e1891f0de525c430a133b661efcf1", "patch": "diff --git a/changes/4037.bugfix.md b/changes/4037.bugfix.md\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 0000000000..f8fa325b5b\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/changes/4037.bugfix.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,1 @@\n+Any `AttributeError` generated by data source `Row` and `Node` objects should reference the correct attribute name.\ndiff --git a/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py b/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\nindex 7adb21b4a5..cfa30a7180 100644\n--- a/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\n+++ b/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\n@@ -90,9 +90,6 @@ def __setattr__(self, attr: str, value: T) -> None:\n             if self._source is not None:\n                 self._source.notify(\"change\", item=self)\n \n-    def __getattr__(self, attr: str) -> T:\n-        return super().__getattr__(attr)\n-\n     def __delattr__(self, attr: str) -> None:\n         \"\"\"Remove an attribute from the Row object, notifying the source of the change.\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "`Row.__getattr__` calls non-existent `super` method\n### Describe the bug\n\nIn the `list_source` module, the `Row` class has a `__getattr__`: https://github.com/corranwebster/toga/blob/64164b5b6eecf79929026a07adf69f84646c4036/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py#L93-L94\n``` python\n    def __getattr__(self, attr: str) -> T:\n        return super().__getattr__(attr)\n```\n\nHowever `Row` is a direct subclass of `object` which *doesn't* have a `__getattr__` method, so the super call will fail likely with a misleading `AttributeError` saying that `__getattr__` is missing rather than the actual attribute which is being requested.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nThe following shows the problem:\n```\n>>> from toga.sources.list_source import Row\n>>> r = Row(a=1)\n>>> r.b\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<python-input-2>\", line 1, in <module>\n    r.b\n  File \"/Users/unital/Developer/toga/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\", line 122, in __getattr__\n    return super().__getattr__(attr)\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\nAttributeError: 'super' object has no attribute '__getattr__'. Did you mean: '__setattr__'?\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBecause `__getattr__` gets called only when an attribute is not found through normal means, either the method should be completely omitted, or if it is needed for typing purposes, then it should raise `AttributeError` directly with the correct attribute name.\n\n### Screenshots\n\n_No response_\n\n### Environment\n\n- Operating System: All\n- Python version: All\n- Software versions:\n  - Toga: current github main branch\n\n\n### Logs\n\n```\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<python-input-2>\", line 1, in <module>\n    r.b\n  File \"/Users/unital/Developer/toga/core/src/toga/sources/list_source.py\", line 122, in __getattr__\n    return super().__getattr__(attr)\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\nAttributeError: 'super' object has no attribute '__getattr__'. Did you mean: '__setattr__'?\n```\n\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/663926b7651daa3488878bcf2bad043b8f0af54c", "https://github.com/beeware/toga/commit/eb84c0fcd6363daab06cd2694927398a1cc7435f"], "created_at": "2025-12-30T12:14:37Z"}
